tists from Bristol]]\n[[Category:Culture jamming]]\n[[Category:English activists]]\n[[Category:English contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:English film directors]]\n[[Category:English satirists]]\n[[Category:Guerilla artists]]\n[[Category:Political artists]]\n[[Category:Pseudonymous artists]]\n[[Category:Street artists]]\n[[Category:Anti-consumerists]]\n[[Category:Unidentified people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Pranksters]]\n[[Category:Album-cover and concert-poster artists]]\n", "name_user": "Pamejudd", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonal life and disputed identity", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Banksy"}
{"title_page": "Birkenhead", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Birkenhead (disambiguation)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{infobox UK place\n|country                  = England\n|official_name            = Liverpool\n|type                     = Town\n|coordinates              = {{coord|53.393|-3.014|display=inline,title}}\n|population               = 88,818\n|population_ref           = ([[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census]])<ref name=ONS2011>{{cite web|url=http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=6507732&c=Birkenhead&d=27&e=62&g=6352177&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1457201783562&enc=1|title=Area: Liverpool(Westminster Parliamentary Constituency)|work=Office for National Statistics|accessdate=5 March 2016}}</ref>\n|area_total_km2           = 25.18\n|area_footnotes           = <ref name=ONS2011 />\n|population_demonym       = Birkonian\n|metropolitan_borough     = [[Metropolitan Borough of Wirral|Wirral]]\n|metropolitan_county      = [[Merseyside]]\n|region                   = North West England\n|static_image_name        = Wirral Museum - old Town Hall, Birkenhead - geograph.org.uk - 237692.jpg\n|static_image_caption     = The former [[Birkenhead Town Hall]] and Wirral Museum, now council offices, committee rooms, and Register Office, in [[Hamilton Square]]\n|constituency_westminster = [[Birkenhead (UK Parliament constituency)|Birkenhead]]\n|post_town                = BIRKENHEAD\n|postcode_district        = CH41, CH42\n|postcode_area            = CH\n|dial_code                = 0151\n|os_grid_reference        = SJ324890\n|london_distance          = {{convert|178|mi|km|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boulter.com/gps/distance/?from=53.393+-3.014&to=51.507+-0.127&units=m|title=Coordinate Distance Calculator|work=boulter.com|accessdate=6 March 2016}}</ref>\n|london_direction         = SE\n|iso_code                 = GB-WRL\n}}\n\n'''Birkenhead''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02cc|b|\u025cr|k|\u0259n|\u02c8|h|\u025b|d}}) is a town in the [[Metropolitan Borough of Wirral]], [[Merseyside]], England. [[Historic counties of England|Historically]] until 1974 in [[Cheshire]], it is on the [[Wirral Peninsula]], along the west bank of the [[River Mersey]], opposite the city of [[Liverpool]].  At the 2011 census, it had a population of 88,818.<ref name=ONS2011/>\n\n[[Birkenhead Priory]] and the [[Mersey Ferry]] were established in the 12th century. In the 19th century, Birkenhead expanded greatly as a consequence of the [[Industrial Revolution]]. [[Birkenhead Park]] and [[Hamilton Square]] were laid out as well as the first street [[tram]]way in Britain. The [[Mersey Railway]] connected Birkenhead and Liverpool, with the world's first tunnel beneath a tidal estuary, and the [[shipbuilding]] firm [[Cammell Laird]] and a [[Great Float|seaport]] were established.\n\nIn the second half of the 20th century, the town suffered a significant period of decline, with [[Containerization|containerisation]] causing a reduction in port activity. The [[Wirral Waters]] development is planned to regenerate much of the dockland.\n\n==Toponymy==\nThe name Birkenhead probably means \"headland overgrown with birch\", from the [[Old English]] {{lang|ang|bircen}} meaning [[birch]] tree,<ref>E. Ekwall, ''The Concise Oxford Dictionary of English Place-Names'', 3rd edn., p.43</ref> of which many once grew on the headland which jutted into the river at [[Woodside, Merseyside|Woodside]]. The name is not derived from [[the Birket]], a stream which enters the Mersey between Birkenhead and Seacombe. The Birket is a later name which was introduced by [[Ordnance Survey]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Wirral Notes and Queries|page=10|date=February 1892|url=https://archive.org/stream/wirralnotesandq00unkngoog#page/n20/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Medieval period===\n[[File:Woodside Ferry Terminal 2006.jpg|thumb|left|The [[Woodside, Merseyside|Woodside]] terminal for the [[Mersey Ferry]] in Birkenhead]]\n[[File:Air Raid Damage in the United Kingdom 1939-1945 H8138.jpg|thumb|left|British troops of [[Western Command (United Kingdom)|Western Command]] clearing up bomb damage in Birkenhead, 15 March 1941.]]\n\nThe earliest records state that the [[Mersey ferry]] began operating from Birkenhead in 1150, when [[Benedictine]] monks under the leadership of [[Hamon de Mascy]] built a [[Birkenhead Priory|priory]] there.<ref>{{citation|title=Birkenhead \u2013 An Illustrated History|first=Ralph T|last=Brocklebank|publisher=Breedon Books|pages=14\u201315|year=2003|isbn=1-85983-350-0}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=http://www.wirral.gov.uk/LGCL/100009/200070/1017/content_0000524.html|title=Birkenhead Priory|publisher=Metropolitan Borough of Wirral|accessdate=14 January 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080304004402/http://www.wirral.gov.uk/LGCL/100009/200070/1017/content_0000524.html|archivedate=4 March 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> The priory was visited in 1275 and 1277 by [[Edward I of England|Edward I]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thebirkenheadpriory.org/history/timeline-of-events|title=Timeline of events|work=Birkenhead Priory|accessdate=5 March 2016}}</ref> In a [[royal charter]] of 13 April 1330, [[Edward III of England|Edward III]] granted the priory further rights.<ref>{{harvnb|Collard|2012|loc=Introduction}}</ref>\n\n===19th century===\nDistanced from the [[Industrial Revolution]] in Liverpool by the physical barrier of the River Mersey, Birkenhead retained its agricultural status until the advent of steam ferry services. In 1817 a steam ferry service started from Liverpool to Tranmere and in 1822 the paddle steamer, ''Royal Mail'', began operation between Liverpool and Woodside.<ref>{{Citation |title =Mersey ferries |url=http://www.liverpoolmuseums.org.uk/maritime/archive/pdf/Ships-Mersey%20Ferries%20no27.pdf |publisher= Liverpool Museums|accessdate=24 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nShipbuilding started in 1829.<ref>{{citation|url=http://nautarch.tamu.edu/PROJECTS/denbigh/Laird.htm|title=Birkenhead-Built: An Unrivaled Historical Legacy|publisher=Institute of Nautical Archaeology at Texas A&M University|accessdate= }}</ref> An iron works was initially established by [[William Laird (shipbuilder)|William Laird]] in 1824 and was joined by his son [[John Laird (shipbuilder)|John Laird]] in 1828. The business eventually became [[Cammell Laird]]. Notable naval vessels built at Birkenhead include [[HMNZS Achilles (70)|HMS ''Achilles'']], {{HMS|Affray|P421|6}}, {{ship|CSS|Alabama}}, {{HMS|Ark Royal|91|6}}, {{HMS|Birkenhead|1845|6}}, {{HMS|Caroline|1914|6}}, {{ship||Hu\u00e1scar|ironclad|2}}, the pioneer submarine {{ship||Resurgam}}, {{HMS|Thetis|N25|6}} (which sank in Liverpool Bay during [[sea trial]]s, and was refloated and [[Ship commissioning|commissioned]] as HMS ''Thunderbolt'', only to be lost to enemy action with the loss of the entire crew), {{HMS|Conqueror|S48|6}} and {{HMS|Prince of Wales|53|6}}. Merchant vessels were also built such as {{RMS|Mauretania|1938|6}} and {{RMS|Windsor Castle|1959|6}}.\n\nIn 1833 an act was passed to introduce street paving, lighting and other improvements in the town. These included establishing a market and regulating the police force.<ref>{{cite book|title=The National Cyclopaedia of Useful Knowledge|volume=Vol. III Bavaria - Caesar|year=1847|location=London|publisher=Charles Knight|page=337|oclc=499316122}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Mersey Railway]] tunnel opened in 1886, providing direct railway access to Liverpool.\n\n===20th century===\nThe [[Grange Road West drill hall, Birkenhead|Grange Road West drill hall]] was completed in 1900.<ref name=drill>{{cite web|url=http://www.drillhalls.org/Counties/Cheshire/TownBirkenhead.htm|title=Birkenhead|publisher=The Drill Halls Project|accessdate=13 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn September 1932 thousands of unemployed people protested in a series of demonstrations organised by the local branch of the [[National Unemployed Workers Movement]]. After three days of rioting, police were brought in from elsewhere to help quell the rioters.<ref>{{citation|last=Kelly|first=S.F.|title=Idle Hands Clenched Fists|publisher=Spokesman Books|date=January 1988|isbn=0-85124-446-7}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the ferries and the railway, the [[Queensway Tunnel|Queensway road tunnel]] opened in 1934 and gave rapid access to Liverpool. This opened up the Wirral Peninsula for development, and prompted further growth of Birkenhead as an industrial centre. Bolstered by migration from rural Cheshire, southern\nIreland and Wales, the town's population had grown from 110 in 1801 to 110,912 one hundred years later and stood at 142,501 by 1951.<ref name=\"Cheshire Towns & Parishes: Birkenhead\">{{citation|url=http://www.ukbmd.org.uk/genuki/chs/birkenhead.html|title=Cheshire Towns & Parishes: Birkenhead|publisher=GENUKI UK & Ireland Genealogy|accessdate=14 January 2008}}</ref>\n\nBirkenhead was struck by [[1981 United Kingdom tornado outbreak|an F0/T1 tornado]] on 23 November 1981, as part of the record-breaking nationwide tornado outbreak on that day.<ref>http://www.eswd.eu/cgi-bin/eswd.cgi</ref>\n\n==Governance==\nFormerly a township in Bidston Parish of the [[Wirral Hundred]], Birkenhead was incorporated as a [[municipal borough]] in 1877, and became a [[county borough]] with the passing of the [[Local Government Act 1888]]. The borough included the parish of Birkenhead St. Mary and the townships of [[Bidston]], [[Claughton, Merseyside|Claughton with Grange]], [[Oxton, Merseyside|Oxton]], [[Tranmere, Merseyside|Tranmere]] and part of [[Bebington]], later known as [[Rock Ferry]].<ref name=\"Cheshire Towns & Parishes: Birkenhead\"/>\nThe townships of [[Landican]], [[Prenton]] and [[Thingwall]] were added in 1928, followed by [[Noctorum]], [[Upton, Merseyside|Upton]] and [[Woodchurch]] in 1933.<ref>{{citation|title=Birkenhead \u2013 An Illustrated History|first=Ralph T|last=Brocklebank|publisher=Breedon Books|page=110|year=2003|isbn=1-85983-350-0}}</ref>\n\nPrior to 1 April 1974, Birkenhead and the rest of the Wirral Peninsula were part of the county of Cheshire. The implementation of the [[Local Government Act 1972]] caused Birkenhead to lose its county borough status. The town has since been administered as part of the [[Metropolitan Borough of Wirral]], in the [[metropolitan county]] of [[Merseyside]].  The Birkenhead and Tranmere [[Wards and electoral divisions of the United Kingdom|electoral ward]] had a population of 15,879 in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukcensusdata.com/birkenhead-and-tranmere-e05000956#sthash.sv2CN2zC.dpbs|title=Ward population 2011|accessdate=31 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe current Member of Parliament for Birkenhead is [[Mick Whitley]].\n\n==Geography==\nThe [[List of conurbations in the United Kingdom|Birkenhead Urban Area]], as defined by the [[Office for National Statistics]],<ref name=\"FOPM_UrbanAreas\">{{citation|url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/downloads/theme_compendia/fom2005/03_FOPM_UrbanAreas.pdf |title=Focus on People & Migration: The UK's major urban areas|publisher=Office for National Statistics|year=2005|accessdate=|archiveurl=https://www.webarchive.org.uk/wayback/archive/20080825051819/http://www.statistics.gov.uk/downloads/theme_compendia/fom2005/03_FOPM_UrbanAreas.pdf|archivedate=25 August 2008}}</ref> includes Birkenhead, [[Wallasey]], Bebington, Ellesmere Port (which is outside the Metropolitan Borough of Wirral) and the contiguous built-up areas which link those towns. In the [[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census]], the area so defined had a total population of 325,264,<ref name=\"BUA\">{{cite web | url=http://www.nomisweb.co.uk/articles/747.aspx|title=2011 Census \u2013 Built-up areas| work= | publisher=[[Office for National Statistics|ONS]] | accessdate=11 August 2013}}</ref> making it the 19th largest [[conurbation]] in England and Wales.\n\n{{Geographic location\n|Northwest = [[Bidston]]<br />[[Upton, Merseyside|Upton]]<br />[[Leasowe]]<br />[[Moreton, Merseyside|Moreton]]\n|North = [[Seacombe]]<br />[[Wallasey]]<br />[[New Brighton, Merseyside|New Brighton]]\n|Northeast = [[Liverpool]]<br />''(across [[River Mersey]])''\n|West = [[Claughton, Merseyside|Claughton]]<br />[[Oxton, Merseyside|Oxton]]\n|Centre = within or near Birkenhead Urban Area\n|East = [[Liverpool]]<br />''(across [[River Mersey]])''\n|Southwest = [[Prenton]]\n|South = [[Tranmere, Merseyside|Tranmere]]<br />[[Bebington]]<br />[[Bromborough]]\n|Southeast = [[Ellesmere Port]]<br />[[Helsby]]<br />\n}}\n\n==Economy==\n\n===Shipbuilding===\n[[File:The Duke of Edinburgh opening the new entrance to the Great Northern Docks at Birkenhead, 1866.png|thumb|left|250px|The Duke of Edinburgh opening the new entrance to the Great Northern Docks at Birkenhead, 1866]]\nShipbuilding and ship repair has featured prominently in the local economy since the 19th century. [[Cammell Laird]] entered [[receivership]] in 2001. The shipyard was sold and became 'Northwestern Shiprepairers & Shipbuilders' (NS&S), which grew into a successful business specialising in ship repair and conversion, including maintenance contracts for the [[Royal Fleet Auxiliary]]. In September 2007 NS&S acquired the rights to use the Cammell Laird name. The company was renamed 'Cammell Laird Shiprepairers & Shipbuilders' on 17 November 2008,<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/liverpool-news/local-news/2008/11/17/cammell-laird-name-returns-on-river-mersey-100252-22275256/ |title=Cammell Laird name returns on River Mersey|author= Neil Hodgson|date=17 November 2008|publisher=[[Liverpool Echo]]|accessdate=19 December 2008}}</ref> seeing the famous name return to Birkenhead after a seven-year hiatus. In 2010, Cammell Laird secured a \u00a350&nbsp;million contract to construct the [[flight deck]] for {{HMS|Queen Elizabeth|R08|6}},<ref>{{cite web |url=\nhttp://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/liverpool-news/local-news/2010/01/25/cammell-laird-wins-50m-royal-navy-warship-contract-100252-25676005/ |title=Cammell Laird wins \u00a350m Royal Navy warship contract|accessdate=25 January 2010 |date=25 January 2010|publisher=[[Liverpool Echo]]}}</ref> the first of two {{sclass-|Queen Elizabeth|aircraft carrier}}s. In 2015, Cammell Laird was selected as the preferred bidder to construct {{ship|RRS|Sir David Attenborough}}, a [[Royal Research Ship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/merseyside-beats-global-competition-to-build-200-million-polar-research-ship|title=Merseyside beats global competition to build \u00a3200 million polar research ship|work=UK Government|date=12 October 2015|accessdate=6 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/polar-research-ship-named-after-11293273|title=Polar research ship to be named after Sir David Attenborough - not Boaty McBoatface|first=Eleanor|last=Barlow|work=Liverpool Echo|date=6 May 2016|accessdate=6 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Commerce===\nBirkenhead Market was first established on what is now the site of [[Birkenhead Town Hall]], between Chester Street and Hamilton Street, on 10 July 1835.<ref name=\"Yesterday's Wirral\">{{citation|title=Yesterday's Wirral|first=Ian & Marilyn|last=Boumphrey|year=1981|isbn=0-9507255-1-X}}</ref><ref name=\"Birkenhead Market: A Brief History\">{{cite web|url=http://www.birkenheadmarket.co.uk/index.asp?page=3|title=Birkenhead Market: A Brief History|accessdate=15 September 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070826173401/http://www.birkenheadmarket.co.uk/index.asp?page=3|archivedate=26 August 2007}}</ref>\nAn increase in the town's population by 1841 led to the opening on 11 July 1845<ref name=\"Birkenhead Market: A Brief History\"/> of a much expanded market on a larger site nearby. This market hall was built by [[Fox, Henderson & Co]], who later built [[The Crystal Palace]].<ref>{{harvnb|Pevsner|Hubbard|1971|p=84}}</ref> [[Michael Marks]], of [[Marks & Spencer]], opened one of his first seven 'Penny Bazaar' stalls here during the 1880s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.knittingtogether.co.uk/doc.asp?doc=7383&cat=745|title=Don't ask the price, it's a penny|work=Knitting Together|accessdate=2 July 2006|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070311011607/http://www.knittingtogether.co.uk/doc.asp?doc=7383&cat=745|archivedate=11 March 2007}}</ref> On 31 January 2018, Marks & Spencer announced the closure of their store, in the town centre of Birkenhead, happening in April.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/marks-spencer-confirms-plans-close-14225927|title=Marks and Spencer confirms plans to close Birkenhead store|work=Liverpool Echo|date=31 January 2018|accessdate=1 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-42886154|title=Marks and Spencer plans to close up to 14 stores|work=BBC News|date=31 January 2018|accessdate=1 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 1970s, the commercial centre of the town was redeveloped around the principal shopping area of Grange Road. Following two fires at the expanded Birkenhead Market in 1969 and 1974, it was moved to new premises adjoining the Grange Shopping Precinct development in 1977.<ref name=Bidston19>{{harvnb|Bidston|1978|page=19}}</ref> Commercial expansion continued in the early 1990s when the Pyramids Shopping Centre was opened.  The previous market site has been redeveloped with the construction of two office buildings, primarily to house [[Land Registry (United Kingdom)|Land Registry]] and [[Department for Work and Pensions]] offices.\n\n===Economic statistics===\nIn February 2010, the town had an overall unemployment rate of 8.2% (males 12.4%, female 4.1%) as against a national average of 4.4%.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/datablog/2009/jan/20/unemployment-statistics-benefit-claimants-constituency-data |title=Unemployment statistics where you live: benefit claimants constituency by constituency |publisher=guardian.co.uk |accessdate=21 March 2010 |department=Business |location=London |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100123145208/http://www.guardian.co.uk/news/datablog/2009/jan/20/unemployment-statistics-benefit-claimants-constituency-data |archivedate=23 January 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Demography==\nIn 2011, Birkenhead had a population of 88,818. The wider Urban Subdivision had a population of over 142,000. However, this latter figure includes areas such as [[Greasby]] and [[Frankby]], which are separate from Birkenhead.\n\nThese are the 2011 ethnic groups for the town:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ukpollingreport.co.uk/2015guide/birkenhead/|title=Birkenhead|work=UK Polling Report|accessdate=17 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n*93.5% [[White British]]\n*2.3% Other White\n*1.2% Mixed Race\n*2.6% [[Asian people|Asian]]\n*0.2% Black\n*0.2% Other\n\n==Landmarks==\n[[File:Birkenhead Park.jpg|thumb|right|Birkenhead Park]]\n[[File:Edward VII Memorial.jpg|thumb|right|Edward VII Memorial Clock Tower, designed by [[Edmund Kirby]].]]\n[[Birkenhead Park]] is acknowledged to be the first publicly funded park in [[Great Britain|Britain]].<ref>{{citation|title=Birkenhead \u2013 An Illustrated History|first=Ralph T|last=Brocklebank|publisher=Breedon Books|page=33|year=2003|isbn=1-85983-350-0}}</ref>\nThe park was the forerunner of the Parks Movement and its influence was far reaching both in Britain and abroad \u2013 most notably on [[Frederick Law Olmsted]]'s design for [[Central Park]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.wirral.gov.uk/LGCL/100006/200073/670/content_0001109.html|title=Birkenhead Park|publisher=Metropolitan Borough of Wirral|accessdate=14 January 2008|isbn=0-7726-3949-3|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080612114530/http://www.wirral.gov.uk/LGCL/100006/200073/670/content_0001109.html|archivedate=12 June 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\nDesigned by [[Joseph Paxton]] (later Sir Joseph Paxton) in 1843 and officially opened in 1847, with great festivity.<ref>{{harvnb|Bidston|1978|p=30}}</ref> The park's [[Grand Entrance to Birkenhead Park|Grand Entrance]], modelled on the Temple of Illysus in Athens,{{citation needed|date=February 2016}} and its 'Roman Boathouse' are notable features. There are sandstone lodges at the three entrances, each with a different style of architecture, [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]], [[Norman architecture|Norman]] and [[Italianate architecture|Italianate]]. There are also two lakes and an ornate 'Swiss Bridge'.\n\n[[William Laird (shipbuilder)|William Laird]], a Scot, and his son [[John Laird (shipbuilder)|John]], were influential in the design of the town. Parts were laid out in a grid-iron pattern like [[New Town, Edinburgh|Edinburgh New Town]] with similar architecture. The chief architect was [[James Gillespie Graham]] from Edinburgh.<ref name=Bidston15>{{harvnb|Bidston|1978|page=15}}</ref> This grid pattern was centred around [[Hamilton Square]] which was started in 1826 and, apart from [[Trafalgar Square]] in London, contains the most [[Grade I listed buildings]] in one place in England.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.wirral.gov.uk/LGCL/100009/200064/10054/content_0002083.html|title=Architecture: Hamilton Square|publisher=Metropolitan Borough of Wirral|accessdate=14 January 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071107015518/http://www.wirral.gov.uk/LGCL/100009/200064/10054/content_0002083.html|archivedate=7 November 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> including [[Birkenhead Town Hall]]. A short distance from Hamilton Square are two other notable landmarks: the [[Queensway Tunnel|Queensway Tunnel Main Entrance]] and the [[Woodside, Merseyside|Woodside Ferry Terminal]]. The film ''[[Chariots of Fire]]'' had scenes shot at Woodside. These scenes were as a representation of [[Dover]] in the 1920s.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.wheredidtheyfilmthat.co.uk/film.php?film_id=60|title=Chariots of Fire|publisher=Where Did They Film That?|accessdate=18 February 2007}}</ref>\n\nOther notable landmarks include [[Bidston Windmill]] on a ridge behind the town, Flaybrick Watertower and [[Birkenhead Priory|Birkenhead Priory & St. Mary's Tower]].\n\n==Transport==\n\n===Trams===\nBirkenhead had the first street tramway in Britain. Opened on 29 August 1860 the first line ran from [[Woodside, Merseyside|Woodside]] (adjoining the terminal of the Mersey Ferry) to [[Birkenhead Park]]. This early system was horse-drawn and was the brainchild of flamboyant American, [[George Francis Train]].<ref name=\"Birkenhead - An Illustrated History\">{{citation|title=Birkenhead \u2013 An Illustrated History|first=Ralph T|last=Brocklebank|publisher=Breedon Books|year=2003|isbn=1-85983-350-0}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=http://www.wirral.gov.uk/LGCL/100009/200070/1017/content_0000522.html|title=Birkenhead Tramway & Wirral Transport Museum|publisher=Metropolitan Borough of Wirral|accessdate=14 January 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080316021142/http://www.wirral.gov.uk/LGCL/100009/200070/1017/content_0000522.html|archivedate=16 March 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\nA preserved tram was on display in the Woodside ferry terminal booking hall.\n\nThe system was later electrified and operated from 1901 as [[Birkenhead Corporation Tramways]]. Two replica trams, imported from Hong Kong, have been brought into service as part of a heritage tramway between Woodside and [[Wirral Transport Museum]], and [[Birkenhead Corporation Tramways]] Car No.20 is preserved on this line.\n\n===Buses===\n{{main|Birkenhead Buses}}\n\nHorse-drawn buses began operating in Birkenhead in 1848, to be replaced with motor vehicles after the [[First World War]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.petergould.co.uk/local_transport_history/fleetlists/birkenhead1.htm |title=Birkenhead Corporation Transport: 1901\u20131969|publisher=ClassicBusDepot.com|accessdate=26 May 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090321141459/http://www.petergould.co.uk/local_transport_history/fleetlists/birkenhead1.htm|archivedate=21 March 2009}}</ref>\n\nPresent-day services are run by operators including [[Arriva North West|Arriva]] and [[Stagecoach]] and coordinated by [[Merseytravel]]. Birkenhead bus station opened in 1996.\n\n[[National Express Coaches|National Express]] provides long-distance coach services to other UK cities, with direct routes including London, Glasgow, [[Bangor, Gwynedd|Bangor]] and [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.carlberry.co.uk/rfnlistr.asp?L1=BIR041&cp=2&srt=O |title=Listing of Transport Services from Birkenhead |publisher=Travel Search|accessdate=26 May 2009}}</ref>\n\n====Birkenhead Bus Station====\n[[File:Birkenhead bus station 4.JPG|thumb|Birkenhead bus station]]\n'''Birkenhead Bus Station''' serves the town of Birkenhead. It is adjacent to The Grange Shopping Centre and Birkenhead Market.\n\nIt has a total of eleven stands and incorporates a travel centre. The main bus operators at the station include [[Arriva North West]], [[Avon Buses]] and [[Stagecoach North West]]\n\nBus services using the bus station operate around the town of Birkenhead, throughout the Wirral, and to the nearby city of [[Liverpool]] via the [[Queensway Tunnel]]. The station also has frequent services to as far away as [[Chester]].\n\n===Railways===\nRailways reached Birkenhead in 1840, when the [[Chester and Birkenhead Railway]] began services.<ref name=DS1>{{cite web|url=http://www.disused-stations.org.uk/b/birkenhead_grange_lane/|title=Station Name: Birkenhead Grange Lane|work=Disused Stations|accessdate=7 March 2016}}</ref> [[Birkenhead Grange Lane railway station]] opened at the same time, becoming the town's first terminus.<ref name=DS1 /> [[Birkenhead Dock railway station]] opened in 1866, as the eastern terminus of the [[Hoylake Railway]].<ref name=DS2>{{cite web|url=http://www.disused-stations.org.uk/b/birkenhead_dock/|title=Station Name: Birkenhead Dock|work=Disused Stations|accessdate=3 March 2016}}</ref> With the opening of the [[Woodside and Birkenhead Dock Street Tramway]] in 1873,<ref name=Maund10>{{harvnb|Maund|2009|p=10}}</ref> this station probably became the world's first [[tram]] to train [[interchange station|interchange]].<ref name=DS2 /> In 1886 Birkenhead and [[Liverpool]] were linked by an [[Rapid transit|underground railway]] system, which today is part of the [[Merseyrail]] network.\n\nThe major underground station in Birkenhead is [[Hamilton Square railway station|Hamilton Square]], the nearest station to the ferry terminal. Hamilton Square station is linked to the \"Liverpool Loop\" of the [[Wirral Line]], which includes [[Liverpool James Street railway station|James Street]], [[Moorfields railway station|Moorfields]], [[Liverpool Lime Street railway station|Liverpool Lime Street]] and [[Liverpool Central railway station|Liverpool Central]] stations, all of which are underground. Other stations located in Birkenhead include [[Birkenhead Central railway station|Birkenhead Central]] which is open but below ground level, [[Green Lane railway station|Green Lane]] which is below ground level, [[Rock Ferry railway station|Rock Ferry]], [[Conway Park railway station|Conway Park]] which is below ground level, [[Birkenhead Park railway station|Birkenhead Park]], [[Birkenhead North railway station|Birkenhead North]] and [[Bidston railway station|Bidston]].\n\nThe Wirral Line from Birkenhead travels south to [[Chester]] and [[Ellesmere Port]], north to [[New Brighton, Merseyside|New Brighton]] and westwards, across the Wirral Peninsula, to [[West Kirby]]. The [[Borderlands Line]] leaves Bidston station, in the north of Birkenhead and travels through the rural centre of Wirral, ultimately leaving England near [[Shotton, Flintshire|Shotton]] and terminating in [[Wrexham]], Wales.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.merseytravel.gov.uk/pdf/MerseyrailNetworkMap.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081230182703/http://www.merseytravel.gov.uk/pdf/MerseyrailNetworkMap.pdf|archivedate=30 December 2008|format=PDF|title=Merseyrail Network Map|url-status=dead|work=Merseytravel}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1878, until its closure in 1967, [[Birkenhead Woodside railway station]] was the town's mainline railway terminus. Originally located close to Woodside Ferry Terminal, the site had been redeveloped as part of [[John Laird (shipbuilder)|Cammell Lairds]] ship builders. Latterly the adjacent dry dock at Cammell Lairds was filled in and the whole area redeveloped to provide flats, a bus depot and offices for [[HM Land Registry]] and [[Child Support Agency]] (CSA).\n\nThe town has one operational railway depot, [[Birkenhead North TMD]]; one disused, [[Birkenhead Central TMD]]; and two demolished, [[Birkenhead Mollington Street TMD]] and a further depot adjacent to Birkenhead Park station. The remains of the [[Birkenhead Dock Branch]] are still extant in a [[Cut (earthmoving)|cutting]] through the centre of the town, which was used primarily for freight services. Much of the peripheral railway infrastructure, around the docks, has been removed since the 1980s.\n\n===Roads===\nJunctions 1 and 3 of the [[M53 motorway]] allow access to the national motorway network. The [[A41 road|A41]] [[trunk road]] connects Woodside with [[Marble Arch]] in London. Two road tunnels, the [[Queensway Tunnel|Queensway road tunnel]] from Birkenhead, and the [[Kingsway Tunnel|Kingsway road tunnel]] from Wallasey, run underneath the River Mersey and connect the town to Liverpool.\n\n===Maritime===\nBirkenhead's [[Great Float|dock system]] is part of the [[Port of Liverpool]], operated by the [[Mersey Docks and Harbour Company]] under the ownership of [[The Peel Group]]. The [[Twelve Quays]] ferry terminal allows a direct freight and passenger vehicle service to [[Dublin]], Ireland and [[Belfast]], Northern Ireland. Daily Belfast services are run by [[Stena Line]], using their [[Roll-on/roll-off#ROPAX|RoPax]] ferries {{MS|Stena Lagan}} and {{MS|Stena Mersey}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/business/mersey-belfast-ferry-operator-close-8924491|title=Mersey to Belfast ferry operator close to completing \u00a36m upgrade on Irish Sea fleet|first=Tony|last=McDonough|work=Liverpool Echo|date=27 March 2015|accessdate=7 March 2016}}</ref> The [[Mersey Ferry]] at Woodside operates a passenger service to Liverpool and chartered cruising.\n\nDuring winter months, the [[Isle of Man Steam Packet Company]] operates a service from Birkenhead to [[Douglas, Isle of Man|Douglas]] using {{MS|Ben-my-Chree}}. Due to weather conditions, this service temporarily replaces the route that normally operates from the Liverpool landing stage using fast craft.\n\n===Aviation===\nThe nearest airport is [[Liverpool John Lennon Airport]] (formerly known as Speke Airport) located about {{convert|8|mi|0|abbr=out}} from Birkenhead. [[Manchester Airport]] is approximately {{convert|40|mi|km|abbr=on}} from Birkenhead. Other nearby aviation facilities include [[Hawarden Airport]] and [[RAF Woodvale]]. Former airfields in the area include [[RAF Hooton Park]] and [[Bidston Aerodrome]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wirralhistory.net/bidstonaerodrome.html|title=Bidston Aerodrome|work=History of The Wirral Hundred or The Wirral Peninsula|accessdate=7 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n\n===Schools===\nBirkenhead has a number of maintained schools, including [[Birkenhead Park School]] (formed after the merger of Rock Ferry High School and Park High School) and the only all-boys Catholic grammar school in the area [[St. Anselm's College]].\n\nBirkenhead also has two independently run schools. The oldest is [[Birkenhead School]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.birkenheadschool.co.uk|title=Birkenhead School|accessdate=2 February 2007|isbn=0-907768-88-1}}</ref> It was exclusively a boys' school from its founding in 1860 until 2000, when its sixth form became co-educational. It became fully co-educational for pupils aged 3\u201318 in 2008.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.wirralglobe.co.uk/search/display.var.1819178.0.school_prepares_to_make_historic_move.php|title=School prepares to make historic move|publisher=[[Wirral Globe]]|date=8 November 2007|accessdate=14 January 2008}}</ref> \"Old Birkonians\" (as former pupils are known) include the lawyer [[Lord Birkenhead|F.E. Smith]] (Lord Birkenhead); [[Andreas Whittam Smith]] (chairman of the [[British Board of Film Classification]] (BBFC) and founder of ''[[The Independent]]'' newspaper); [[Andrew Irvine (mountaineer)|Andrew Irvine]], and [[Philip Toosey]], hero at the [[Bridge on the River Kwai]]; and [[Tony Hall, Baron Hall of Birkenhead|Tony Hall]], [[Director-General of the BBC]].\n\n[[Birkenhead High School Academy]], formerly Birkenhead Girls High School, is an all-ability state funded girls' [[Academy (English school)|Academy]]. It was founded in 1885 and caters for girls aged 3\u201319. Its sponsor was the [[Girls' Day School Trust]], but is now publicly funded. Its alumnae include the actress [[Patricia Routledge]]. Birkenhead Girls High School decided to become a state-funded [[Academy (England)|Academy]] school in 2009, increasing the availability of its education.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.liverpooldailypost.co.uk/liverpool-news/regional-news/2009/11/20/wirral-s-birkenhead-high-school-academy-told-to-cater-for-the-poorest-92534-25211679|title=Wirral's Birkenhead High School Academy told to cater for the poorest|work=Liverpool Daily Post|first=Kevin|last=Core|date=20 November 2009|accessdate=4 December 2009}}</ref> Like the change to co-education at Birkenhead School, this decision was largely driven by falling pupil numbers;{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}} however to this date, it remains a single sex school.\n\nBirkenhead Institute Grammar School existed from 1889 in Whetstone Lane, before being moved to Claughton in the 1970s. The school closed in 1994.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://biwirral.webs.com/|title=Birkenhead Institute, Wirral|work=Spirit of Birkenhead Institute|accessdate=31 August 2016}}</ref> The school's alumni include [[Wilfred Owen]].\n\n===Colleges===\nPreviously situated at Borough Road, Birkenhead's college has campuses at Europa Boulevard and Twelve Quays. The college was originally Birkenhead Technical College, and has been known as [[Wirral Metropolitan College]] since the 1980s.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}} The college had a theatre on Borough Road named after one of its most famous former students, [[Glenda Jackson]], the [[Academy Awards|Oscar]]-winning actress and Member of Parliament, herself a Birkonian, born in 1936. The Borough Road campus and the Glenda Jackson Theatre were demolished in late 2005, to make way for [[Apartment|flats]], although Wirral Metropolitan College flourishes on other sites across Wirral. The theatre secretly housed an emergency command centre for the region in its basement, accessible via the college.<ref name=\"bunker\">{{cite web|url=http://www.subbrit.org.uk/rsg/sites/b/birkenhead/|title=Site Name: Birkenhead - Wirral Metropolitan Borough Emergency Centre/Merseyside County Standby (Site 2)|work=Subterranea Britannica|accessdate=1 November 2015}}</ref> Politicians and officials would have retreated to this secure [[bunker]] in the event of nuclear war to co-ordinate the recovery effort. By the 1990s, after the end of the [[Cold War]], the bunker had been decommissioned and the surrounding complex of rooms was used by the college as a rehearsal space and recording studio.<ref name=\"bunker\" />\n\nOther colleges include the [[Birkenhead Sixth Form College]], located in the Claughton area of Birkenhead, formerly the site of Corpus Christi Catholic High School.\n\n==Religion==\n[[File:St James' Church, Birkenhead - DSC04377.JPG|thumb|right|St James' Church]]\nReligion in Birkenhead dates back to 1150 when Hamon de Masci founded [[Birkenhead Priory]] for the [[Benedictine]] order.\n\nThe current [[Anglican]] churches are [[St James' Church, Birkenhead|St. James' Church]], [[Christ Church, Birkenhead|Christ Church]] and the [[Church of Christ the King, Birkenhead|Church of Christ the King]] which are all within the [[Diocese of Chester]]. [[Keith Sinclair (bishop)|Keith Sinclair]] is the [[Suffragan bishop|suffragan]] [[Bishop of Birkenhead]].\n\n[[Roman Catholic]] churches include the [[Church of Our Lady of the Immaculate Conception, Birkenhead|Church of Our Lady of the Immaculate Conception]] and [[St Werburgh's Church, Birkenhead|St. Werburgh's Church]] which are within the [[Diocese of Shrewsbury]].\n\nThe other religious buildings include the [[Wirral Christian Centre]] of the [[Elim Pentecostal Church]] and the [[Islamic]] Shah Jalal [[Mosque]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mosquedirectory.co.uk/mosques/england/merseyside/liverpool/birkenhead/Wirral-Islamic-Cultural-Centre-and-Shah-Jalal-Mosque-Birkenhead-Liverpool-Merseyside/2939|title=Wirral Islamic Cultural Centre and Shah Jalal Mosque|work=mosquedirectory.co.uk|accessdate=13 February 2016}}</ref> The [[Jewish]] Birkenhead [[Synagogue]] existed from 1890 and closed prior to 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishgen.org/jcr-uk/Community/birken/index.htm|title=Birkenhead Synagogue|work=JCR-UK|accessdate=13 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[Flaybrick Hill Cemetery|Flaybrick Memorial Gardens]] contains the town's former main cemetery, which is situated near to St. James' Church. Flaybrick Hill Cemetery has been superseded by [[Landican#Landican Cemetery|Landican Cemetery]].\n\n==Healthcare==\nBirkenhead has one of the highest mortality rates among men over 65 in the UK.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wirralnews.co.uk/wirral-news/local-wirral-news/2009/12/04/bootle-pensioners-have-lowest-life-expectancy-in-uk-with-birkenhead-oaps-not-far-behind-100252-25322826|title=Bootle pensioners have shortest life expectancy in UK with Birkenhead OAPs also in bottom ten|publisher=Wirral News|date=4 December 2009|accessdate=4 December 2009|first=Jo|last=Kelly|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110809192557/http://www.wirralnews.co.uk/wirral-news/local-wirral-news/2009/12/04/bootle-pensioners-have-lowest-life-expectancy-in-uk-with-birkenhead-oaps-not-far-behind-100252-25322826/|archivedate=9 August 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> Birkenhead is served by [[Wirral University Teaching Hospital NHS Foundation Trust]] (through its [[Arrowe Park Hospital]], [[St Catherine's Health Centre]] and [[Clatterbridge Hospital]] sites) and Wirral [[Primary Care Trust]]. Formerly, Birkenhead was also served by [[Birkenhead General Hospital]] on Park Road North and St. James' Hospital in Claughton, now demolished and redeveloped for housing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/hospitalrecords/details.asp?id=816&page=58|title= St James' Hospital, Birkenhead|publisher=National archives|accessdate=11 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Arts and leisure==\n\n===Arts===\nThe [[Laird School of Art]] was the first public school of art outside London and was given to the town by John Laird. It opened on 27 September 1871. The [[Williamson Art Gallery and Museum|Williamson Art Gallery]] was opened in 1928 and houses a fine collection of paintings, porcelain and pottery.\n\nIn 1856, Birkenhead Library was opened as the country's first public library in an [[Unincorporated area|unincorporated]] borough.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.visitliverpool.com/site/product-p44389|title=Birkenhead Central Library|publisher=visitliverpool.com|accessdate=14 January 2008}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\nThe library was situated in Hamilton Street until 1909, when it moved to a new building in Market Street South,<ref name=Bidston23>{{harvnb|Bidston|1978|page=23}}</ref> near Birkenhead Market. In the 1930s, this building (along with much of the surrounding area) was demolished to make way for the entrance to the [[Queensway Tunnel]]. The present library, [[Birkenhead Central Library]], is situated on Borough Road and was opened by [[George V of the United Kingdom|King George V]] in 1934.<ref name=Bidston23 />\n\nDespite being in England, Birkenhead (known as ''Penbedw'', in Welsh) hosted Wales' [[National Eisteddfod]] in 1917<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.archiveshub.ac.uk/aug04e.shtml|title=Title page of the 1917 Welsh National Eisteddfod programme held at Birkenhead|publisher=Archives Hub|accessdate=18 February 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070525192426/http://www.archiveshub.ac.uk/aug04e.shtml|archivedate=25 May 2007}}</ref> as well as an unofficial National Eisteddfod event in 1879. As in Liverpool,<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/northeast/sites/history/pages/liverpool.shtml|title=The Liverpool Welsh|publisher=BBC Wales|date=7 January 2008|accessdate=14 January 2008}}</ref> migrants from Wales, especially North Wales, contributed greatly to the growth of the town and its cultural development in the 19th century. The first local Birkenhead Eisteddfod, a precursor of the national events, took place in 1864.<ref>{{cite book|title=Liverpool 800: Culture, Character & History|editor=John Belchem|year=2006|isbn=1-84631-035-0}}</ref> The 1917 National Eisteddfod was notable for the award of the chair to the poet Ellis Humphrey Evans, known as [[Hedd Wyn]]. The winner was announced, and the crowd waited for the winner to accept congratulations before the chairing ceremony, but no winner appeared. It was then announced that Hedd Wyn had been killed the previous month on the battlefield in Belgium, and the bardic chair was draped in black. These events were portrayed in the [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] nominated film ''[[Hedd Wyn (film)|Hedd Wyn]]'', and were apparently intended as a protest against the war policies of [[Prime Minister of the UK|Prime Minister]] [[David Lloyd George]], who was present. There is a commemorative stone for the event in Birkenhead Park.<ref>{{cite book|first=Stephen J.|last=Roberts|title=A History of Wirral|year=2002|isbn=978-1-86077-512-3}}</ref> The first meeting of the international [[Celtic Congress]] also took place at the Birkenhead Eisteddfod.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.evertype.com/celtcong/cc-hist-mellis.html |title=A short history of the Celtic Congress|first=Mari|last=Ellis|accessdate=3 October 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080602125805/http://www.evertype.com/celtcong/cc-hist-mellis.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2 June 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Argyle Theatre]] was a major theatre and music hall which opened on 28 December 1868<ref name=Bidston19 /> and became notable for the calibre of artistes who appeared there. Later in its life, it was also used as a cinema. The theatre was destroyed by bombing in 1940.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.arthurlloyd.co.uk/BirkenheadTheatres.htm|title=Birkenhead, Wirral, Theatres and Halls|publisher=arthurlloyd.co.uk|accessdate=16 July 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Theatre Royal'', opened on 31 October 1864, was in Argyle Street and had a capacity of 1,850.<ref name=Bidston19 /> This theatre was closed in 1919 and demolished in the 1930s.<ref name=Bidston19 /> Another theatre, the ''Hippodrome'', which was converted into a cinema in the 1930s, stood on the site of what became the [[The Co-operative Group|Co-operative]] department store in Grange Road.<ref name=Bidston20>{{harvnb|Bidston|1978|page=20}}</ref>\n\nThe Little Theatre was established in 1958 from a converted former [[Presbyterian]] church whilst, more recently, the Pacific Road Arts Centre in Woodside opened in 1999.\n\n===Media===\nBirkenhead is served by the ''[[Liverpool Echo]]'' local daily newspaper. The free local weekly newspapers are the ''Wirral Globe'' and the ''Birkenhead News'' (part of the Wirral News group).\n\nThe local radio station [[Heart Wirral]] is based in offices at the Pacific Road Arts Centre. In addition, there are five other local radio stations that transmit to Birkenhead: [[BBC Radio Merseyside]], [[Radio City 96.7]], [[Greatest Hits Liverpool]], [[Capital Liverpool]] and [[City Talk 105.9|CityTalk]].\n\nBirkenhead is situated within the television regions of [[BBC]] North West and [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]'s [[Granada Television]]. The local television station [[Bay TV Liverpool]] also broadcasts to the area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wirralglobe.co.uk/news/11646943.Bay_TV_Liverpool_to_make_a_splash_today/|title=Bay TV Liverpool to make a splash today|work=Wirral Globe|date=4 December 2014|accessdate=2 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Leisure===\nAs well as Birkenhead Park, other recreational open spaces in Birkenhead include Mersey Park and Victoria Park. [[Arrowe Park]] is a large area of parkland at the western edge of the town. In 1929, the [[3rd World Scout Jamboree]] was held there.\n\nThe first two [[Scouting|Boy Scout]] groups in the world are thought to have been founded as the 1st and 2nd Birkenhead groups at [[YMCA]] on the same night in 1908.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://2ndbirkenhead.webs.com/|title=Home|website=2nd Birkenhead Scout Group|access-date=2018-11-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181112101413/https://2ndbirkenhead.webs.com/|archive-date=12 November 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> The 2nd Birkenhead Scout Group is still operating and therefore is the longest running scout group in the world.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\n===Sport===\nThe first known [[association football|football]]  club on the Wirral was Birkenhead F.C. which was founded in 1879 by Robert E. Lythgoe, a former [[Druids F.C.]] player. Other clubs included Belmont Football Club, founded in 1884.  They adopted the name [[Tranmere Rovers F.C.]] the following year, and are a professional team who play at [[Prenton Park]] near the Tranmere area of the town. They were a founder member of [[Football League Third Division North|Division Three North]] in 1921, and were a member of [[The Football League]] until 2015, when they were relegated to the [[Football Conference|Conference]], the fifth tier of English football. They returned to the Football League three seasons later, after a 2-1 play off final win against [[Boreham Wood F.C.]].  (An unrelated, disbanded side had played under the name \"Tranmere Rovers Cricket Club (Association football section)\" in 1881\u201382.) [[Cammell Laird 1907 F.C.]] is the town's semi-professional [[association football|football]] club who play at Kirklands in Rock Ferry. They play in the [[North West Counties League]] Division One.\n\nThe [[Birkenhead Park FC|Birkenhead Park Football Club]] was founded in 1871, the same year as the [[Rugby Football Union]]. The club originally played in the Lower Park but moved to their current home in the Upper Park in 1885.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pitchero.com/clubs/birkenheadpark/a/a-brief-history-of-birkenhead-park-41151.html |title=A BRIEF HISTORY OF BIRKENHEAD PARK|work=Pitchero|accessdate=23 November 2015}}</ref> Birkenhead Park also has its own [[cricket]] club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pitchero.com/clubs/birkenheadparkcricketclub|title=Welcome|work=Pitchero|accessdate=1 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nLocated in the town are the Birkenhead North End and Victoria Cycling Clubs. Olympic riders from the clubs include [[Chris Boardman]], [[Mark Bell (cyclist)|Mark Bell]], [[Steve Cummings]] and [[Rachel Heal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bnecc.co.uk/about_us.htm|title=Birkenhead North End Cycling Club Olympians|accessdate=18 February 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071008215259/http://www.bnecc.co.uk/about_us.htm|archivedate=8 October 2007|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://fp.marklw.plus.com/htdocs/bvcc/theclub/history.htm|title=Birkenhead Victoria Cycling Club history |accessdate=18 February 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050107022728/http://fp.marklw.plus.com/htdocs/bvcc/theclub/history.htm|archivedate=7 January 2005}}</ref>\n\nBirkenhead has been host to various [[Rowing (sport)|rowing]] clubs since 1840.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.merseyrc.com/page11.htm|title=The History of Mersey Rowing Club: Founded 1854|work=Mersey Rowing Club|accessdate=5 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160505062910/http://www.merseyrc.com/page11.htm|archive-date=5 May 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> At present, Liverpool Victoria Rowing Club operates from a facility at the western end of West Float.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.britishrowing.org/club/liverpool-victoria-rc/|title=Liverpool Victoria RC|work=British Rowing|accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Cultural references==\nBirkenhead is mentioned in the song \"What She Said\" on the album ''[[Meat Is Murder]]'' by [[the Smiths]]: ''What she read/All heady books/She'd sit and prophesise{{not a typo}}/(It took a tattooed boy from Birkenhead/To really really open her eyes).''\n\nThe town is also referred to in the song \"Everything Is Sorrow\" on the [[The Boo Radleys|Boo Radleys]]' ''[[C'mon Kids]]'' album: ''I worked in Birkenhead for you/It brings me tears even now.''\n\nA fairly detailed description of the town is given in [[Paul O'Grady]]'s memoirs, ''At My Mother's Knee ... and Other Low Joints: The Autobiography''.\n\nBirkenhead is indirectly referenced by \"''the Birken'ead drill''\" in [[Rudyard Kipling]]'s poem \"Soldier an' Sailor Too\": ''To take your chance in the thick of a rush, with firing all about, / Is nothing so bad when you've cover to 'and, an' leave an' likin' to shout; / But to stand an' be still to the Birken'ead drill is a damn tough bullet to chew, / An' they done it, the Jollies \u2013 'Er Majesty's Jollies \u2013 soldier an' sailor too!'', as it refers to heroism by Royal Marines during the sinking of [[HMS Birkenhead (1845)|HMS Birkenhead]], itself named after the town in which it was built.  [[HMS Birkenhead (1845)#Aftermath|Other authors]] have done this as well.\n\nThe 1998 book, [[Awaydays]], and the following 2009 film of the same name are set in Birkenhead.\n\n==Notable people==\n===Actors and performers===\nIn the arts, Birkenhead has produced several actors and performers including [[Lionel Gamlin]], [[Glenda Jackson]],<ref name=\"liverpoolecho.co.uk\">http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/all-about/birkenhead</ref> [[Lewis Collins]], [[Megs Jenkins]], [[Taron Egerton]], [[Patricia Routledge]], [[Paul O'Grady]] (also known as [[Lily Savage]]) and soprano [[Valerie Masterson]]. The dancer and actor [[Lindsay Kemp]] was born in the town but as a child moved to [[South Shields]].<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/features/lindsay-kemp-how-the-lost-boy-of-dance-found-his-feet-9188679.html  Nadine Meisner, \"Lindsay Kemp: How the lost boy of dance found his feet\", ''The Independent'', 28 January 2002]. Retrieved 25 August 2018</ref>\n\n===Artists===\nSome notable artists were born in the town, such as [[Philip Wilson Steer]], [[Robert Talbot Kelly]], [[Tom Palin]], [[Bessie Bamber]], [[Annie R. Merrylees Arnold]], the workers at the [[Della Robbia Pottery]] and two cartoonists: [[Norman Thelwell]] and [[Bill Tidy]].<ref>https://www.pressreader.com/uk/cheshire-life/20181001/283025465549093</ref>\n\n===Authors and journalists===\nIt has also produced poets and authors such as [[A.S.J. Tessimond]], [[Adrian Henri]] and Michael Z. Williamson. The [[World War I]] poet [[Wilfred Owen]], though born in [[Oswestry]], lived in Birkenhead from the age of 4 and was educated at the Birkenhead Institute High School (now demolished). [[Andreas Whittam Smith]], founder editor of ''[[The Independent]]'', grew up in Birkenhead, where his father was an [[Anglican]] clergyman.<ref>{{citation|title=Why I am Still an Anglican|publisher=Continuum|year=2006|page=67}}</ref>\n\n===Musicians===\nThere are several musicians linked to the area. [[Freddie Marks]] from [[Rod, Jane and Freddy]] was born in Birkenhead, as was [[John Gorman (entertainer)|John Gorman]] of [[The Scaffold]]. Indie band [[Half Man Half Biscuit]] hail from Birkenhead, as did boogie-rock band [[Engine (boogie-rock band)|Engine]], [[Paul Heaton]], lead singer of the [[Housemartins]] and the [[Beautiful South]], singer/songwriter [[Charlie Landsborough]] and [[Desmond Briscoe]] co-founder and original manager of the pioneering [[BBC Radiophonic Workshop]]. [[Elvis Costello]] moved to Birkenhead in 1971 with his mother,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/whats-on/music-nightlife-news/elvis-costello-publish-memoirs-8954761|first=Jade|last=Wright|title=Elvis Costello to publish his memoirs|work=Liverpool Echo|date=31 March 2015|accessdate=29 October 2015}}</ref> who was from Liverpool, although Elvis Costello's father was himself from Birkenhead. [[Tony Friel]] (bassist from [[The Fall (band)|the Fall]] and [[The Passage (band)|the Passage]]), synthpop musician [[David Hughes (musician)|David Hughes]] (of [[Dalek I Love You]], [[Orchestral Manoeuvres in the Dark]] and [[Godot (band)|Godot]]) and [[Malcolm Holmes]] (drummer with pop group [[Orchestral Manoeuvres in the Dark]]) were born there. [[David Balfe]] (music manager, and member of Dalek I Love You, [[Big in Japan (band)|Big in Japan]], [[the Teardrop Explodes]]) attended primary and secondary school there. [[Miles Kane]], musician, singer and songwriter and member of [[The Last Shadow Puppets]] and [[The Rascals (English band)|The Rascals]], was born in the town.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n\n===Politicians and public figures===\n[[File:The Rt Hon. Frederick Edwin Smith, 1st Earl of Birkenhead in 1915.jpg|thumb|[[F. E. Smith, 1st Earl of Birkenhead]]]]\n[[F. E. Smith, 1st Earl of Birkenhead]], a leading Conservative politician of the early 20th century, was born in the town, as were [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] politician [[Malcolm Bruce]], [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] politician [[Stephen Ladyman]], the prominent [[occult]]ist [[Alex Sanders (Wiccan)|Alex Sanders]], and [[Tony Hall, Baron Hall of Birkenhead]], the [[Director-General of the BBC]].\n\n===Scientists and technologists===\nAerodynamicists [[Gwen Alston]] and [[Melvill Jones]] were born in Birkenhead, as was [[David Pearson (computer scientist)|David Pearson]] hitech pioneer. Also born in Birkenhead was [[Henry Herbert Collier]], inventor and founder of the [[Matchless]] motorcycle marque.\n\n===Soldiers and explorers===\n[[Sandy Irvine]], a participant of the [[1924 British Mount Everest expedition]], was born in Birkenhead. There has been speculation that [[George Mallory]] and he reached the summit. Similarly, [[Alan Rouse]], a mountaineer who died in the [[1986 K2 disaster]], was educated in Birkenhead. [[Daniel Poole]], a recipient of the [[Distinguished Conduct Medal]] during [[World War I]] was born in the town.<ref name=ADB>Foldi, N.S. (1978). [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A110261b.htm Poole, Daniel (1882\u20131959)']. [[Australian Dictionary of Biography]], Volume 11, Melbourne University Press, p. 255. Retrieved on 9 August 2009.</ref>\n\n===Sports people===\nBirkenhead has also produced notable sportsmen such as [[Matt Dawson]], the [[rugby union]] player; [[William Ralph Dean|'Dixie' Dean]] ([[Everton F.C.]]),<ref name=\"liverpoolecho.co.uk\"/> record-breaking footballer, who was born at 313 Laird Street; and several other footballers including [[Peter Davenport]], [[Jason McAteer]], [[David Thompson (footballer, born 1977)|David Thompson]], [[Max Power (footballer)|Max]] [[Max Power (footballer)|Power]], [[Jodie Taylor]] England Lionesses International .The football manager [[Nigel Adkins]] also hails from the town International relations.\n\n==Twin towns==\nBirkenhead is [[Town twinning|twinned]], as a part of [[Metropolitan Borough of Wirral|Wirral]], with:\n*{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Gennevilliers]], France\n*{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Latina, Lazio]], Italy\n*{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Lorient]], France\n\n===Twin towns \u2013 Sister cities===\nBirkenhead also has a [[Sister City|Sister City Agreement]] with:\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Midland, Texas|Midland]], [[Texas]], United States<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.wirral.gov.uk/LGCL/100009/200096/662/content_0002058.html|archive-url=https://archive.is/20070703053914/http://www.wirral.gov.uk/LGCL/100009/200096/662/content_0002058.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=3 July 2007|title=Town Twinning|publisher=Metropolitan Borough of Wirral|accessdate=14 January 2008|isbn=92-827-8272-7}}</ref>\n\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in the United Kingdom}}\n\n==Future==\nThe major redevelopment project under consideration is [[Peel Holdings]]' \"[[Wirral Waters]]\". This would allow for \u00a34.5&nbsp;billion of investment in the regeneration of the dockland area. This equates with an investment of over \u00a314,000 for each of the 320,000 residents of the Wirral. At the [[Great Float|East Float]] and [[Vittoria Dock]], the development would include several 50-storey skyscrapers, {{convert|5000000|sqft|m2|-3}} of new office space and {{convert|11000000|sqft|m2}} for new residential flats. A retail and leisure quarter at the former [[Bidston Dock]] site would encompass another {{convert|571000|sqft|m2|-2}} of space. The whole project would create more than 27,000 permanent new jobs, aside from the employment required for construction and other peripheral employment. The development would be expected to take up to thirty years.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.peel.co.uk/peelholdings/source/newsdetails.asp?type=1&page=1&newsid=122|title=Peel unveil plans for \u00a34.5 billion \"Wirral Waters\" scheme|publisher=Peel Holdings|date=5 September 2006|accessdate=14 January 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071011034738/http://www.peel.co.uk/peelholdings/source/newsdetails.asp?type=1&page=1&newsid=122 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 11 October 2007}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Listed buildings in Birkenhead]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n*{{cite book|title=Birkenhead in Times Past|first=Carol E.|last=Bidston|publisher=Countryside Publications Ltd.|location=Chorley|year=1978|isbn=0861570030|oclc=16480899|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|title=Birkenhead Through Time|first=Ian|last=Collard|publisher=Amberley|year=2012|isbn=9781848689657|oclc=934954016|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book| title=The Wirral Railway and its Predecessors| year=2009| first=T.B. |last=Maund| publisher=Lightmoor Press| isbn=978-1-899889-38-9|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|first1=Nikolaus|last1=Pevsner|authorlink1=Nikolaus Pevsner|first2=Edward|last2=Hubbard|authorlink2=Edward Hubbard|title=Cheshire|series=The Buildings of England|publisher=Penguin|year=1971|isbn=9780140710427|oclc=521341|ref=harv}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|title=Birkenhead and its Surroundings|first=Henry Kelsall|last=Aspinall|publisher=The Liverpool Booksellers' Co. Ltd.|location=Liverpool|date=1903|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S3IKAwAAQBAJ|oclc=33990938}}\n*{{cite book|title=Yesterday's Wirral: Birkenhead, Prenton and Oxton|first1=Ian|last1=Boumphrey|first2=Marilyn|last2=Boumphrey|publisher=Ian & Marilyn Boumphrey|year=1981|isbn=9780950725512|oclc=16599808}}\n*{{cite book|title=Birkenhead: A Pictorial History|first=Ian|last=Boumphrey|publisher=Phillmore|year=1995|isbn=9780850339888|oclc=36548684}}\n*{{cite book|title=Yesterday's Birkenhead|first=Ian|last=Boumphrey|publisher=The author|year=2007a|isbn=9781899241262}}\n*{{cite book|title=Birkenhead at War 1939-45|first=Ian|last=Boumphrey|publisher=Ian & Marilyn Boumphrey|year=2007b|isbn=9781899241163|oclc=650238915}}\n*{{cite book|title=Annals of the Liverpool Stage|pp=377\u2013386|first=R.J.|last=Broadbent|publisher=Edward Howell|location=Liverpool|year=1908|url=https://archive.org/stream/cu31924026123822#page/n437/mode/2up/search/birkenhead}}\n*{{cite book|title=Birkenhead: An Illustrated History|first=Ralph T.|last=Brocklebank|publisher=Breedon|year=2003|isbn=9781859833506|oclc=56469838}}\n*{{cite book|title=Birkenhead from old photographs|first=Ian|last=Collard|publisher=Amberley|year=2010|isbn=9781848685796|oclc=503647633}}\n*{{cite book|title=Birkenhead: A History|first=Elizabeth|last=Davey|publisher=The History Press|year=2013|isbn=9780750955522|oclc=316434050}}\n*{{cite book|title=Memories of the chronicles of Birkenhead|first=Hilda|last=Gamlin|publisher=E. Howell|year=1892|oclc=866209732}}\n*{{cite book|title=A Century of Birkenhead and Wirral|first=Cliff|last=Hayes|publisher=Sutton|year=2007|isbn=9780750949040|oclc=520460751}}\n*{{cite book|title=Birkenhead Shipbuilding|first=Alan G.|last=Jones|publisher=Fast Print|year=2011|isbn= \t9781780352114|oclc=773368902}}\n*{{cite book|title=Bygone Birkenhead|first=J.R.|last=Kaighin|publisher=Wilmer|year=1925|oclc=77304339}}\n*{{cite book|title=Birkenhead, 1877-1974|first=Myrra|last=Lea|publisher=County Borough of Birkenhead|year=1974|isbn=9780904582000|oclc=1365533}}\n*{{cite book|title=Meat at Woodside: Birkenhead Livestock Trade, 1878-1981|first=Ken|last=McCarron|publisher=Merseyside Port Folios|year=1991|isbn=9780951612927|oclc=26313657}}\n*{{cite book|title=Birkenhead yesterday and today|first=W.R.S.|last=McIntyre|publisher=Philip|year=1948|oclc=504769644}}\n*{{cite book|title=The History of the Hundred of Wirral|first=William Williams|last=Mortimer|year=1847|publisher=Whittaker & Co.|location=London|url=https://archive.org/stream/historyhundredw01mortgoog#page/n346/mode/2up|id=pp305\u2013405|oclc=4976662}}\n*{{cite book|title=Reminiscences of Birkenhead|first=Charles Grey|last=Mott|publisher=H. Young and Sons|year=1900|isbn=|oclc=12987941}}\n*{{cite book|title=Report on Secondary Education in Birkenhead|first=Michael E.|last=Sadler|publisher=George Philip & Son Ltd.|location=London|year=1904|url=https://archive.org/stream/reportonseconda04sadlgoog#page/n5/mode/2up}}\n*{{cite book|title=History of ancient and modern Birkenhead|first=Philip|last=Sulley|publisher=W.M. Murphy|year=1907|oclc=29557494}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.wirralhistory.com/Birkenhead.html Birkenhead & Surrounds]\n{{Commons category|Birkenhead}}\n{{Wikivoyage}}\n{{Wikisource1911Enc|Birkenhead}}\n\n{{Birkenhead}}\n\n{{Populated Places in Wirral Borough}}\n{{Merseyside}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Birkenhead| ]]\n[[Category:Port cities and towns in North West England]]\n[[Category:Port cities and towns of the Irish Sea]]\n[[Category:Towns and villages in the Metropolitan Borough of Wirral]]\n[[Category:Towns in Merseyside]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Birkenhead (disambiguation)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{infobox UK place\n|country                  = England\n|official_name            = Birkenhead\n|type                     = Town\n|coordinates              = {{coord|53.393|-3.014|display=inline,title}}\n|population               = 88,818\n|population_ref           = ([[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census]])<ref name=ONS2011>{{cite web|url=http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=6507732&c=Birkenhead&d=27&e=62&g=6352177&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1457201783562&enc=1|title=Area: Birkenhead (Westminster Parliamentary Constituency)|work=Office for National Statistics|accessdate=5 March 2016}}</ref>\n|area_total_km2           = 25.18\n|area_footnotes           = <ref name=ONS2011 />\n|population_demonym       = Birkonian\n|metropolitan_borough     = [[Metropolitan Borough of Wirral|Wirral]]\n|metropolitan_county      = [[Merseyside]]\n|region                   = North West England\n|static_image_name        = Wirral Museum - old Town Hall, Birkenhead - geograph.org.uk - 237692.jpg\n|static_image_caption     = The former [[Birkenhead Town Hall]] and Wirral Museum, now council offices, committee rooms, and Register Office, in [[Hamilton Square]]\n|constituency_westminster = [[Birkenhead (UK Parliament constituency)|Birkenhead]]\n|post_town                = BIRKENHEAD\n|postcode_district        = CH41, CH42\n|postcode_area            = CH\n|dial_code                = 0151\n|os_grid_reference        = SJ324890\n|london_distance          = {{convert|178|mi|km|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boulter.com/gps/distance/?from=53.393+-3.014&to=51.507+-0.127&units=m|title=Coordinate Distance Calculator|work=boulter.com|accessdate=6 March 2016}}</ref>\n|london_direction         = SE\n|iso_code                 = GB-WRL\n}}\n\n'''Birkenhead''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02cc|b|\u025cr|k|\u0259n|\u02c8|h|\u025b|d}}) is a town in the [[Metropolitan Borough of Wirral]], [[Merseyside]], England. [[Historic counties of England|Historically]] until 1974 in [[Cheshire]], it is on the [[Wirral Peninsula]], along the west bank of the [[River Mersey]], opposite the city of [[Liverpool]].  At the 2011 census, it had a population of 88,818.<ref name=ONS2011/>\n\n[[Birkenhead Priory]] and the [[Mersey Ferry]] were established in the 12th century. In the 19th century, Birkenhead expanded greatly as a consequence of the [[Industrial Revolution]]. [[Birkenhead Park]] and [[Hamilton Square]] were laid out as well as the first street [[tram]]way in Britain. The [[Mersey Railway]] connected Birkenhead and Liverpool, with the world's first tunnel beneath a tidal estuary, and the [[shipbuilding]] firm [[Cammell Laird]] and a [[Great Float|seaport]] were established.\n\nIn the second half of the 20th century, the town suffered a significant period of decline, with [[Containerization|containerisation]] causing a reduction in port activity. The [[Wirral Waters]] development is planned to regenerate much of the dockland.\n\n==Toponymy==\nThe name Birkenhead probably means \"headland overgrown with birch\", from the [[Old English]] {{lang|ang|bircen}} meaning [[birch]] tree,<ref>E. Ekwall, ''The Concise Oxford Dictionary of English Place-Names'', 3rd edn., p.43</ref> of which many once grew on the headland which jutted into the river at [[Woodside, Merseyside|Woodside]]. The name is not derived from [[the Birket]], a stream which enters the Mersey between Birkenhead and Seacombe. The Birket is a later name which was introduced by [[Ordnance Survey]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Wirral Notes and Queries|page=10|date=February 1892|url=https://archive.org/stream/wirralnotesandq00unkngoog#page/n20/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Medieval period===\n[[File:Woodside Ferry Terminal 2006.jpg|thumb|left|The [[Woodside, Merseyside|Woodside]] terminal for the [[Mersey Ferry]] in Birkenhead]]\n[[File:Air Raid Damage in the United Kingdom 1939-1945 H8138.jpg|thumb|left|British troops of [[Western Command (United Kingdom)|Western Command]] clearing up bomb damage in Birkenhead, 15 March 1941.]]\n\nThe earliest records state that the [[Mersey ferry]] began operating from Birkenhead in 1150, when [[Benedictine]] monks under the leadership of [[Hamon de Mascy]] built a [[Birkenhead Priory|priory]] there.<ref>{{citation|title=Birkenhead \u2013 An Illustrated History|first=Ralph T|last=Brocklebank|publisher=Breedon Books|pages=14\u201315|year=2003|isbn=1-85983-350-0}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=http://www.wirral.gov.uk/LGCL/100009/200070/1017/content_0000524.html|title=Birkenhead Priory|publisher=Metropolitan Borough of Wirral|accessdate=14 January 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080304004402/http://www.wirral.gov.uk/LGCL/100009/200070/1017/content_0000524.html|archivedate=4 March 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> The priory was visited in 1275 and 1277 by [[Edward I of England|Edward I]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thebirkenheadpriory.org/history/timeline-of-events|title=Timeline of events|work=Birkenhead Priory|accessdate=5 March 2016}}</ref> In a [[royal charter]] of 13 April 1330, [[Edward III of England|Edward III]] granted the priory further rights.<ref>{{harvnb|Collard|2012|loc=Introduction}}</ref>\n\n===19th century===\nDistanced from the [[Industrial Revolution]] in Liverpool by the physical barrier of the River Mersey, Birkenhead retained its agricultural status until the advent of steam ferry services. In 1817 a steam ferry service started from Liverpool to Tranmere and in 1822 the paddle steamer, ''Royal Mail'', began operation between Liverpool and Woodside.<ref>{{Citation |title =Mersey ferries |url=http://www.liverpoolmuseums.org.uk/maritime/archive/pdf/Ships-Mersey%20Ferries%20no27.pdf |publisher= Liverpool Museums|accessdate=24 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nShipbuilding started in 1829.<ref>{{citation|url=http://nautarch.tamu.edu/PROJECTS/denbigh/Laird.htm|title=Birkenhead-Built: An Unrivaled Historical Legacy|publisher=Institute of Nautical Archaeology at Texas A&M University|accessdate= }}</ref> An iron works was initially established by [[William Laird (shipbuilder)|William Laird]] in 1824 and was joined by his son [[John Laird (shipbuilder)|John Laird]] in 1828. The business eventually became [[Cammell Laird]]. Notable naval vessels built at Birkenhead include [[HMNZS Achilles (70)|HMS ''Achilles'']], {{HMS|Affray|P421|6}}, {{ship|CSS|Alabama}}, {{HMS|Ark Royal|91|6}}, {{HMS|Birkenhead|1845|6}}, {{HMS|Caroline|1914|6}}, {{ship||Hu\u00e1scar|ironclad|2}}, the pioneer submarine {{ship||Resurgam}}, {{HMS|Thetis|N25|6}} (which sank in Liverpool Bay during [[sea trial]]s, and was refloated and [[Ship commissioning|commissioned]] as HMS ''Thunderbolt'', only to be lost to enemy action with the loss of the entire crew), {{HMS|Conqueror|S48|6}} and {{HMS|Prince of Wales|53|6}}. Merchant vessels were also built such as {{RMS|Mauretania|1938|6}} and {{RMS|Windsor Castle|1959|6}}.\n\nIn 1833 an act was passed to introduce street paving, lighting and other improvements in the town. These included establishing a market and regulating the police force.<ref>{{cite book|title=The National Cyclopaedia of Useful Knowledge|volume=Vol. III Bavaria - Caesar|year=1847|location=London|publisher=Charles Knight|page=337|oclc=499316122}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Mersey Railway]] tunnel opened in 1886, providing direct railway access to Liverpool.\n\n===20th century===\nThe [[Grange Road West drill hall, Birkenhead|Grange Road West drill hall]] was completed in 1900.<ref name=drill>{{cite web|url=http://www.drillhalls.org/Counties/Cheshire/TownBirkenhead.htm|title=Birkenhead|publisher=The Drill Halls Project|accessdate=13 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn September 1932 thousands of unemployed people protested in a series of demonstrations organised by the local branch of the [[National Unemployed Workers Movement]]. After three days of rioting, police were brought in from elsewhere to help quell the rioters.<ref>{{citation|last=Kelly|first=S.F.|title=Idle Hands Clenched Fists|publisher=Spokesman Books|date=January 1988|isbn=0-85124-446-7}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the ferries and the railway, the [[Queensway Tunnel|Queensway road tunnel]] opened in 1934 and gave rapid access to Liverpool. This opened up the Wirral Peninsula for development, and prompted further growth of Birkenhead as an industrial centre. Bolstered by migration from rural Cheshire, southern\nIreland and Wales, the town's population had grown from 110 in 1801 to 110,912 one hundred years later and stood at 142,501 by 1951.<ref name=\"Cheshire Towns & Parishes: Birkenhead\">{{citation|url=http://www.ukbmd.org.uk/genuki/chs/birkenhead.html|title=Cheshire Towns & Parishes: Birkenhead|publisher=GENUKI UK & Ireland Genealogy|accessdate=14 January 2008}}</ref>\n\nBirkenhead was struck by [[1981 United Kingdom tornado outbreak|an F0/T1 tornado]] on 23 November 1981, as part of the record-breaking nationwide tornado outbreak on that day.<ref>http://www.eswd.eu/cgi-bin/eswd.cgi</ref>\n\n==Governance==\nFormerly a township in Bidston Parish of the [[Wirral Hundred]], Birkenhead was incorporated as a [[municipal borough]] in 1877, and became a [[county borough]] with the passing of the [[Local Government Act 1888]]. The borough included the parish of Birkenhead St. Mary and the townships of [[Bidston]], [[Claughton, Merseyside|Claughton with Grange]], [[Oxton, Merseyside|Oxton]], [[Tranmere, Merseyside|Tranmere]] and part of [[Bebington]], later known as [[Rock Ferry]].<ref name=\"Cheshire Towns & Parishes: Birkenhead\"/>\nThe townships of [[Landican]], [[Prenton]] and [[Thingwall]] were added in 1928, followed by [[Noctorum]], [[Upton, Merseyside|Upton]] and [[Woodchurch]] in 1933.<ref>{{citation|title=Birkenhead \u2013 An Illustrated History|first=Ralph T|last=Brocklebank|publisher=Breedon Books|page=110|year=2003|isbn=1-85983-350-0}}</ref>\n\nPrior to 1 April 1974, Birkenhead and the rest of the Wirral Peninsula were part of the county of Cheshire. The implementation of the [[Local Government Act 1972]] caused Birkenhead to lose its county borough status. The town has since been administered as part of the [[Metropolitan Borough of Wirral]], in the [[metropolitan county]] of [[Merseyside]].  The Birkenhead and Tranmere [[Wards and electoral divisions of the United Kingdom|electoral ward]] had a population of 15,879 in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukcensusdata.com/birkenhead-and-tranmere-e05000956#sthash.sv2CN2zC.dpbs|title=Ward population 2011|accessdate=31 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe current Member of Parliament for Birkenhead is [[Mick Whitley]].\n\n==Geography==\nThe [[List of conurbations in the United Kingdom|Birkenhead Urban Area]], as defined by the [[Office for National Statistics]],<ref name=\"FOPM_UrbanAreas\">{{citation|url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/downloads/theme_compendia/fom2005/03_FOPM_UrbanAreas.pdf |title=Focus on People & Migration: The UK's major urban areas|publisher=Office for National Statistics|year=2005|accessdate=|archiveurl=https://www.webarchive.org.uk/wayback/archive/20080825051819/http://www.statistics.gov.uk/downloads/theme_compendia/fom2005/03_FOPM_UrbanAreas.pdf|archivedate=25 August 2008}}</ref> includes Birkenhead, [[Wallasey]], Bebington, Ellesmere Port (which is outside the Metropolitan Borough of Wirral) and the contiguous built-up areas which link those towns. In the [[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census]], the area so defined had a total population of 325,264,<ref name=\"BUA\">{{cite web | url=http://www.nomisweb.co.uk/articles/747.aspx|title=2011 Census \u2013 Built-up areas| work= | publisher=[[Office for National Statistics|ONS]] | accessdate=11 August 2013}}</ref> making it the 19th largest [[conurbation]] in England and Wales.\n\n{{Geographic location\n|Northwest = [[Bidston]]<br />[[Upton, Merseyside|Upton]]<br />[[Leasowe]]<br />[[Moreton, Merseyside|Moreton]]\n|North = [[Seacombe]]<br />[[Wallasey]]<br />[[New Brighton, Merseyside|New Brighton]]\n|Northeast = [[Liverpool]]<br />''(across [[River Mersey]])''\n|West = [[Claughton, Merseyside|Claughton]]<br />[[Oxton, Merseyside|Oxton]]\n|Centre = within or near Birkenhead Urban Area\n|East = [[Liverpool]]<br />''(across [[River Mersey]])''\n|Southwest = [[Prenton]]\n|South = [[Tranmere, Merseyside|Tranmere]]<br />[[Bebington]]<br />[[Bromborough]]\n|Southeast = [[Ellesmere Port]]<br />[[Helsby]]<br />\n}}\n\n==Economy==\n\n===Shipbuilding===\n[[File:The Duke of Edinburgh opening the new entrance to the Great Northern Docks at Birkenhead, 1866.png|thumb|left|250px|The Duke of Edinburgh opening the new entrance to the Great Northern Docks at Birkenhead, 1866]]\nShipbuilding and ship repair has featured prominently in the local economy since the 19th century. [[Cammell Laird]] entered [[receivership]] in 2001. The shipyard was sold and became 'Northwestern Shiprepairers & Shipbuilders' (NS&S), which grew into a successful business specialising in ship repair and conversion, including maintenance contracts for the [[Royal Fleet Auxiliary]]. In September 2007 NS&S acquired the rights to use the Cammell Laird name. The company was renamed 'Cammell Laird Shiprepairers & Shipbuilders' on 17 November 2008,<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/liverpool-news/local-news/2008/11/17/cammell-laird-name-returns-on-river-mersey-100252-22275256/ |title=Cammell Laird name returns on River Mersey|author= Neil Hodgson|date=17 November 2008|publisher=[[Liverpool Echo]]|accessdate=19 December 2008}}</ref> seeing the famous name return to Birkenhead after a seven-year hiatus. In 2010, Cammell Laird secured a \u00a350&nbsp;million contract to construct the [[flight deck]] for {{HMS|Queen Elizabeth|R08|6}},<ref>{{cite web |url=\nhttp://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/liverpool-news/local-news/2010/01/25/cammell-laird-wins-50m-royal-navy-warship-contract-100252-25676005/ |title=Cammell Laird wins \u00a350m Royal Navy warship contract|accessdate=25 January 2010 |date=25 January 2010|publisher=[[Liverpool Echo]]}}</ref> the first of two {{sclass-|Queen Elizabeth|aircraft carrier}}s. In 2015, Cammell Laird was selected as the preferred bidder to construct {{ship|RRS|Sir David Attenborough}}, a [[Royal Research Ship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/merseyside-beats-global-competition-to-build-200-million-polar-research-ship|title=Merseyside beats global competition to build \u00a3200 million polar research ship|work=UK Government|date=12 October 2015|accessdate=6 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/polar-research-ship-named-after-11293273|title=Polar research ship to be named after Sir David Attenborough - not Boaty McBoatface|first=Eleanor|last=Barlow|work=Liverpool Echo|date=6 May 2016|accessdate=6 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Commerce===\nBirkenhead Market was first established on what is now the site of [[Birkenhead Town Hall]], between Chester Street and Hamilton Street, on 10 July 1835.<ref name=\"Yesterday's Wirral\">{{citation|title=Yesterday's Wirral|first=Ian & Marilyn|last=Boumphrey|year=1981|isbn=0-9507255-1-X}}</ref><ref name=\"Birkenhead Market: A Brief History\">{{cite web|url=http://www.birkenheadmarket.co.uk/index.asp?page=3|title=Birkenhead Market: A Brief History|accessdate=15 September 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070826173401/http://www.birkenheadmarket.co.uk/index.asp?page=3|archivedate=26 August 2007}}</ref>\nAn increase in the town's population by 1841 led to the opening on 11 July 1845<ref name=\"Birkenhead Market: A Brief History\"/> of a much expanded market on a larger site nearby. This market hall was built by [[Fox, Henderson & Co]], who later built [[The Crystal Palace]].<ref>{{harvnb|Pevsner|Hubbard|1971|p=84}}</ref> [[Michael Marks]], of [[Marks & Spencer]], opened one of his first seven 'Penny Bazaar' stalls here during the 1880s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.knittingtogether.co.uk/doc.asp?doc=7383&cat=745|title=Don't ask the price, it's a penny|work=Knitting Together|accessdate=2 July 2006|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070311011607/http://www.knittingtogether.co.uk/doc.asp?doc=7383&cat=745|archivedate=11 March 2007}}</ref> On 31 January 2018, Marks & Spencer announced the closure of their store, in the town centre of Birkenhead, happening in April.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/marks-spencer-confirms-plans-close-14225927|title=Marks and Spencer confirms plans to close Birkenhead store|work=Liverpool Echo|date=31 January 2018|accessdate=1 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-42886154|title=Marks and Spencer plans to close up to 14 stores|work=BBC News|date=31 January 2018|accessdate=1 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 1970s, the commercial centre of the town was redeveloped around the principal shopping area of Grange Road. Following two fires at the expanded Birkenhead Market in 1969 and 1974, it was moved to new premises adjoining the Grange Shopping Precinct development in 1977.<ref name=Bidston19>{{harvnb|Bidston|1978|page=19}}</ref> Commercial expansion continued in the early 1990s when the Pyramids Shopping Centre was opened.  The previous market site has been redeveloped with the construction of two office buildings, primarily to house [[Land Registry (United Kingdom)|Land Registry]] and [[Department for Work and Pensions]] offices.\n\n===Economic statistics===\nIn February 2010, the town had an overall unemployment rate of 8.2% (males 12.4%, female 4.1%) as against a national average of 4.4%.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/datablog/2009/jan/20/unemployment-statistics-benefit-claimants-constituency-data |title=Unemployment statistics where you live: benefit claimants constituency by constituency |publisher=guardian.co.uk |accessdate=21 March 2010 |department=Business |location=London |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100123145208/http://www.guardian.co.uk/news/datablog/2009/jan/20/unemployment-statistics-benefit-claimants-constituency-data |archivedate=23 January 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Demography==\nIn 2011, Birkenhead had a population of 88,818. The wider Urban Subdivision had a population of over 142,000. However, this latter figure includes areas such as [[Greasby]] and [[Frankby]], which are separate from Birkenhead.\n\nThese are the 2011 ethnic groups for the town:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ukpollingreport.co.uk/2015guide/birkenhead/|title=Birkenhead|work=UK Polling Report|accessdate=17 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n*93.5% [[White British]]\n*2.3% Other White\n*1.2% Mixed Race\n*2.6% [[Asian people|Asian]]\n*0.2% Black\n*0.2% Other\n\n==Landmarks==\n[[File:Birkenhead Park.jpg|thumb|right|Birkenhead Park]]\n[[File:Edward VII Memorial.jpg|thumb|right|Edward VII Memorial Clock Tower, designed by [[Edmund Kirby]].]]\n[[Birkenhead Park]] is acknowledged to be the first publicly funded park in [[Great Britain|Britain]].<ref>{{citation|title=Birkenhead \u2013 An Illustrated History|first=Ralph T|last=Brocklebank|publisher=Breedon Books|page=33|year=2003|isbn=1-85983-350-0}}</ref>\nThe park was the forerunner of the Parks Movement and its influence was far reaching both in Britain and abroad \u2013 most notably on [[Frederick Law Olmsted]]'s design for [[Central Park]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.wirral.gov.uk/LGCL/100006/200073/670/content_0001109.html|title=Birkenhead Park|publisher=Metropolitan Borough of Wirral|accessdate=14 January 2008|isbn=0-7726-3949-3|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080612114530/http://www.wirral.gov.uk/LGCL/100006/200073/670/content_0001109.html|archivedate=12 June 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\nDesigned by [[Joseph Paxton]] (later Sir Joseph Paxton) in 1843 and officially opened in 1847, with great festivity.<ref>{{harvnb|Bidston|1978|p=30}}</ref> The park's [[Grand Entrance to Birkenhead Park|Grand Entrance]], modelled on the Temple of Illysus in Athens,{{citation needed|date=February 2016}} and its 'Roman Boathouse' are notable features. There are sandstone lodges at the three entrances, each with a different style of architecture, [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]], [[Norman architecture|Norman]] and [[Italianate architecture|Italianate]]. There are also two lakes and an ornate 'Swiss Bridge'.\n\n[[William Laird (shipbuilder)|William Laird]], a Scot, and his son [[John Laird (shipbuilder)|John]], were influential in the design of the town. Parts were laid out in a grid-iron pattern like [[New Town, Edinburgh|Edinburgh New Town]] with similar architecture. The chief architect was [[James Gillespie Graham]] from Edinburgh.<ref name=Bidston15>{{harvnb|Bidston|1978|page=15}}</ref> This grid pattern was centred around [[Hamilton Square]] which was started in 1826 and, apart from [[Trafalgar Square]] in London, contains the most [[Grade I listed buildings]] in one place in England.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.wirral.gov.uk/LGCL/100009/200064/10054/content_0002083.html|title=Architecture: Hamilton Square|publisher=Metropolitan Borough of Wirral|accessdate=14 January 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071107015518/http://www.wirral.gov.uk/LGCL/100009/200064/10054/content_0002083.html|archivedate=7 November 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> including [[Birkenhead Town Hall]]. A short distance from Hamilton Square are two other notable landmarks: the [[Queensway Tunnel|Queensway Tunnel Main Entrance]] and the [[Woodside, Merseyside|Woodside Ferry Terminal]]. The film ''[[Chariots of Fire]]'' had scenes shot at Woodside. These scenes were as a representation of [[Dover]] in the 1920s.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.wheredidtheyfilmthat.co.uk/film.php?film_id=60|title=Chariots of Fire|publisher=Where Did They Film That?|accessdate=18 February 2007}}</ref>\n\nOther notable landmarks include [[Bidston Windmill]] on a ridge behind the town, Flaybrick Watertower and [[Birkenhead Priory|Birkenhead Priory & St. Mary's Tower]].\n\n==Transport==\n\n===Trams===\nBirkenhead had the first street tramway in Britain. Opened on 29 August 1860 the first line ran from [[Woodside, Merseyside|Woodside]] (adjoining the terminal of the Mersey Ferry) to [[Birkenhead Park]]. This early system was horse-drawn and was the brainchild of flamboyant American, [[George Francis Train]].<ref name=\"Birkenhead - An Illustrated History\">{{citation|title=Birkenhead \u2013 An Illustrated History|first=Ralph T|last=Brocklebank|publisher=Breedon Books|year=2003|isbn=1-85983-350-0}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=http://www.wirral.gov.uk/LGCL/100009/200070/1017/content_0000522.html|title=Birkenhead Tramway & Wirral Transport Museum|publisher=Metropolitan Borough of Wirral|accessdate=14 January 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080316021142/http://www.wirral.gov.uk/LGCL/100009/200070/1017/content_0000522.html|archivedate=16 March 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\nA preserved tram was on display in the Woodside ferry terminal booking hall.\n\nThe system was later electrified and operated from 1901 as [[Birkenhead Corporation Tramways]]. Two replica trams, imported from Hong Kong, have been brought into service as part of a heritage tramway between Woodside and [[Wirral Transport Museum]], and [[Birkenhead Corporation Tramways]] Car No.20 is preserved on this line.\n\n===Buses===\n{{main|Birkenhead Buses}}\n\nHorse-drawn buses began operating in Birkenhead in 1848, to be replaced with motor vehicles after the [[First World War]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.petergould.co.uk/local_transport_history/fleetlists/birkenhead1.htm |title=Birkenhead Corporation Transport: 1901\u20131969|publisher=ClassicBusDepot.com|accessdate=26 May 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090321141459/http://www.petergould.co.uk/local_transport_history/fleetlists/birkenhead1.htm|archivedate=21 March 2009}}</ref>\n\nPresent-day services are run by operators including [[Arriva North West|Arriva]] and [[Stagecoach]] and coordinated by [[Merseytravel]]. Birkenhead bus station opened in 1996.\n\n[[National Express Coaches|National Express]] provides long-distance coach services to other UK cities, with direct routes including London, Glasgow, [[Bangor, Gwynedd|Bangor]] and [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.carlberry.co.uk/rfnlistr.asp?L1=BIR041&cp=2&srt=O |title=Listing of Transport Services from Birkenhead |publisher=Travel Search|accessdate=26 May 2009}}</ref>\n\n====Birkenhead Bus Station====\n[[File:Birkenhead bus station 4.JPG|thumb|Birkenhead bus station]]\n'''Birkenhead Bus Station''' serves the town of Birkenhead. It is adjacent to The Grange Shopping Centre and Birkenhead Market.\n\nIt has a total of eleven stands and incorporates a travel centre. The main bus operators at the station include [[Arriva North West]], [[Avon Buses]] and [[Stagecoach North West]]\n\nBus services using the bus station operate around the town of Birkenhead, throughout the Wirral, and to the nearby city of [[Liverpool]] via the [[Queensway Tunnel]]. The station also has frequent services to as far away as [[Chester]].\n\n===Railways===\nRailways reached Birkenhead in 1840, when the [[Chester and Birkenhead Railway]] began services.<ref name=DS1>{{cite web|url=http://www.disused-stations.org.uk/b/birkenhead_grange_lane/|title=Station Name: Birkenhead Grange Lane|work=Disused Stations|accessdate=7 March 2016}}</ref> [[Birkenhead Grange Lane railway station]] opened at the same time, becoming the town's first terminus.<ref name=DS1 /> [[Birkenhead Dock railway station]] opened in 1866, as the eastern terminus of the [[Hoylake Railway]].<ref name=DS2>{{cite web|url=http://www.disused-stations.org.uk/b/birkenhead_dock/|title=Station Name: Birkenhead Dock|work=Disused Stations|accessdate=3 March 2016}}</ref> With the opening of the [[Woodside and Birkenhead Dock Street Tramway]] in 1873,<ref name=Maund10>{{harvnb|Maund|2009|p=10}}</ref> this station probably became the world's first [[tram]] to train [[interchange station|interchange]].<ref name=DS2 /> In 1886 Birkenhead and [[Liverpool]] were linked by an [[Rapid transit|underground railway]] system, which today is part of the [[Merseyrail]] network.\n\nThe major underground station in Birkenhead is [[Hamilton Square railway station|Hamilton Square]], the nearest station to the ferry terminal. Hamilton Square station is linked to the \"Liverpool Loop\" of the [[Wirral Line]], which includes [[Liverpool James Street railway station|James Street]], [[Moorfields railway station|Moorfields]], [[Liverpool Lime Street railway station|Liverpool Lime Street]] and [[Liverpool Central railway station|Liverpool Central]] stations, all of which are underground. Other stations located in Birkenhead include [[Birkenhead Central railway station|Birkenhead Central]] which is open but below ground level, [[Green Lane railway station|Green Lane]] which is below ground level, [[Rock Ferry railway station|Rock Ferry]], [[Conway Park railway station|Conway Park]] which is below ground level, [[Birkenhead Park railway station|Birkenhead Park]], [[Birkenhead North railway station|Birkenhead North]] and [[Bidston railway station|Bidston]].\n\nThe Wirral Line from Birkenhead travels south to [[Chester]] and [[Ellesmere Port]], north to [[New Brighton, Merseyside|New Brighton]] and westwards, across the Wirral Peninsula, to [[West Kirby]]. The [[Borderlands Line]] leaves Bidston station, in the north of Birkenhead and travels through the rural centre of Wirral, ultimately leaving England near [[Shotton, Flintshire|Shotton]] and terminating in [[Wrexham]], Wales.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.merseytravel.gov.uk/pdf/MerseyrailNetworkMap.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081230182703/http://www.merseytravel.gov.uk/pdf/MerseyrailNetworkMap.pdf|archivedate=30 December 2008|format=PDF|title=Merseyrail Network Map|url-status=dead|work=Merseytravel}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1878, until its closure in 1967, [[Birkenhead Woodside railway station]] was the town's mainline railway terminus. Originally located close to Woodside Ferry Terminal, the site had been redeveloped as part of [[John Laird (shipbuilder)|Cammell Lairds]] ship builders. Latterly the adjacent dry dock at Cammell Lairds was filled in and the whole area redeveloped to provide flats, a bus depot and offices for [[HM Land Registry]] and [[Child Support Agency]] (CSA).\n\nThe town has one operational railway depot, [[Birkenhead North TMD]]; one disused, [[Birkenhead Central TMD]]; and two demolished, [[Birkenhead Mollington Street TMD]] and a further depot adjacent to Birkenhead Park station. The remains of the [[Birkenhead Dock Branch]] are still extant in a [[Cut (earthmoving)|cutting]] through the centre of the town, which was used primarily for freight services. Much of the peripheral railway infrastructure, around the docks, has been removed since the 1980s.\n\n===Roads===\nJunctions 1 and 3 of the [[M53 motorway]] allow access to the national motorway network. The [[A41 road|A41]] [[trunk road]] connects Woodside with [[Marble Arch]] in London. Two road tunnels, the [[Queensway Tunnel|Queensway road tunnel]] from Birkenhead, and the [[Kingsway Tunnel|Kingsway road tunnel]] from Wallasey, run underneath the River Mersey and connect the town to Liverpool.\n\n===Maritime===\nBirkenhead's [[Great Float|dock system]] is part of the [[Port of Liverpool]], operated by the [[Mersey Docks and Harbour Company]] under the ownership of [[The Peel Group]]. The [[Twelve Quays]] ferry terminal allows a direct freight and passenger vehicle service to [[Dublin]], Ireland and [[Belfast]], Northern Ireland. Daily Belfast services are run by [[Stena Line]], using their [[Roll-on/roll-off#ROPAX|RoPax]] ferries {{MS|Stena Lagan}} and {{MS|Stena Mersey}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/business/mersey-belfast-ferry-operator-close-8924491|title=Mersey to Belfast ferry operator close to completing \u00a36m upgrade on Irish Sea fleet|first=Tony|last=McDonough|work=Liverpool Echo|date=27 March 2015|accessdate=7 March 2016}}</ref> The [[Mersey Ferry]] at Woodside operates a passenger service to Liverpool and chartered cruising.\n\nDuring winter months, the [[Isle of Man Steam Packet Company]] operates a service from Birkenhead to [[Douglas, Isle of Man|Douglas]] using {{MS|Ben-my-Chree}}. Due to weather conditions, this service temporarily replaces the route that normally operates from the Liverpool landing stage using fast craft.\n\n===Aviation===\nThe nearest airport is [[Liverpool John Lennon Airport]] (formerly known as Speke Airport) located about {{convert|8|mi|0|abbr=out}} from Birkenhead. [[Manchester Airport]] is approximately {{convert|40|mi|km|abbr=on}} from Birkenhead. Other nearby aviation facilities include [[Hawarden Airport]] and [[RAF Woodvale]]. Former airfields in the area include [[RAF Hooton Park]] and [[Bidston Aerodrome]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wirralhistory.net/bidstonaerodrome.html|title=Bidston Aerodrome|work=History of The Wirral Hundred or The Wirral Peninsula|accessdate=7 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n\n===Schools===\nBirkenhead has a number of maintained schools, including [[Birkenhead Park School]] (formed after the merger of Rock Ferry High School and Park High School) and the only all-boys Catholic grammar school in the area [[St. Anselm's College]].\n\nBirkenhead also has two independently run schools. The oldest is [[Birkenhead School]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.birkenheadschool.co.uk|title=Birkenhead School|accessdate=2 February 2007|isbn=0-907768-88-1}}</ref> It was exclusively a boys' school from its founding in 1860 until 2000, when its sixth form became co-educational. It became fully co-educational for pupils aged 3\u201318 in 2008.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.wirralglobe.co.uk/search/display.var.1819178.0.school_prepares_to_make_historic_move.php|title=School prepares to make historic move|publisher=[[Wirral Globe]]|date=8 November 2007|accessdate=14 January 2008}}</ref> \"Old Birkonians\" (as former pupils are known) include the lawyer [[Lord Birkenhead|F.E. Smith]] (Lord Birkenhead); [[Andreas Whittam Smith]] (chairman of the [[British Board of Film Classification]] (BBFC) and founder of ''[[The Independent]]'' newspaper); [[Andrew Irvine (mountaineer)|Andrew Irvine]], and [[Philip Toosey]], hero at the [[Bridge on the River Kwai]]; and [[Tony Hall, Baron Hall of Birkenhead|Tony Hall]], [[Director-General of the BBC]].\n\n[[Birkenhead High School Academy]], formerly Birkenhead Girls High School, is an all-ability state funded girls' [[Academy (English school)|Academy]]. It was founded in 1885 and caters for girls aged 3\u201319. Its sponsor was the [[Girls' Day School Trust]], but is now publicly funded. Its alumnae include the actress [[Patricia Routledge]]. Birkenhead Girls High School decided to become a state-funded [[Academy (England)|Academy]] school in 2009, increasing the availability of its education.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.liverpooldailypost.co.uk/liverpool-news/regional-news/2009/11/20/wirral-s-birkenhead-high-school-academy-told-to-cater-for-the-poorest-92534-25211679|title=Wirral's Birkenhead High School Academy told to cater for the poorest|work=Liverpool Daily Post|first=Kevin|last=Core|date=20 November 2009|accessdate=4 December 2009}}</ref> Like the change to co-education at Birkenhead School, this decision was largely driven by falling pupil numbers;{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}} however to this date, it remains a single sex school.\n\nBirkenhead Institute Grammar School existed from 1889 in Whetstone Lane, before being moved to Claughton in the 1970s. The school closed in 1994.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://biwirral.webs.com/|title=Birkenhead Institute, Wirral|work=Spirit of Birkenhead Institute|accessdate=31 August 2016}}</ref> The school's alumni include [[Wilfred Owen]].\n\n===Colleges===\nPreviously situated at Borough Road, Birkenhead's college has campuses at Europa Boulevard and Twelve Quays. The college was originally Birkenhead Technical College, and has been known as [[Wirral Metropolitan College]] since the 1980s.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}} The college had a theatre on Borough Road named after one of its most famous former students, [[Glenda Jackson]], the [[Academy Awards|Oscar]]-winning actress and Member of Parliament, herself a Birkonian, born in 1936. The Borough Road campus and the Glenda Jackson Theatre were demolished in late 2005, to make way for [[Apartment|flats]], although Wirral Metropolitan College flourishes on other sites across Wirral. The theatre secretly housed an emergency command centre for the region in its basement, accessible via the college.<ref name=\"bunker\">{{cite web|url=http://www.subbrit.org.uk/rsg/sites/b/birkenhead/|title=Site Name: Birkenhead - Wirral Metropolitan Borough Emergency Centre/Merseyside County Standby (Site 2)|work=Subterranea Britannica|accessdate=1 November 2015}}</ref> Politicians and officials would have retreated to this secure [[bunker]] in the event of nuclear war to co-ordinate the recovery effort. By the 1990s, after the end of the [[Cold War]], the bunker had been decommissioned and the surrounding complex of rooms was used by the college as a rehearsal space and recording studio.<ref name=\"bunker\" />\n\nOther colleges include the [[Birkenhead Sixth Form College]], located in the Claughton area of Birkenhead, formerly the site of Corpus Christi Catholic High School.\n\n==Religion==\n[[File:St James' Church, Birkenhead - DSC04377.JPG|thumb|right|St James' Church]]\nReligion in Birkenhead dates back to 1150 when Hamon de Masci founded [[Birkenhead Priory]] for the [[Benedictine]] order.\n\nThe current [[Anglican]] churches are [[St James' Church, Birkenhead|St. James' Church]], [[Christ Church, Birkenhead|Christ Church]] and the [[Church of Christ the King, Birkenhead|Church of Christ the King]] which are all within the [[Diocese of Chester]]. [[Keith Sinclair (bishop)|Keith Sinclair]] is the [[Suffragan bishop|suffragan]] [[Bishop of Birkenhead]].\n\n[[Roman Catholic]] churches include the [[Church of Our Lady of the Immaculate Conception, Birkenhead|Church of Our Lady of the Immaculate Conception]] and [[St Werburgh's Church, Birkenhead|St. Werburgh's Church]] which are within the [[Diocese of Shrewsbury]].\n\nThe other religious buildings include the [[Wirral Christian Centre]] of the [[Elim Pentecostal Church]] and the [[Islamic]] Shah Jalal [[Mosque]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mosquedirectory.co.uk/mosques/england/merseyside/liverpool/birkenhead/Wirral-Islamic-Cultural-Centre-and-Shah-Jalal-Mosque-Birkenhead-Liverpool-Merseyside/2939|title=Wirral Islamic Cultural Centre and Shah Jalal Mosque|work=mosquedirectory.co.uk|accessdate=13 February 2016}}</ref> The [[Jewish]] Birkenhead [[Synagogue]] existed from 1890 and closed prior to 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishgen.org/jcr-uk/Community/birken/index.htm|title=Birkenhead Synagogue|work=JCR-UK|accessdate=13 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[Flaybrick Hill Cemetery|Flaybrick Memorial Gardens]] contains the town's former main cemetery, which is situated near to St. James' Church. Flaybrick Hill Cemetery has been superseded by [[Landican#Landican Cemetery|Landican Cemetery]].\n\n==Healthcare==\nBirkenhead has one of the highest mortality rates among men over 65 in the UK.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wirralnews.co.uk/wirral-news/local-wirral-news/2009/12/04/bootle-pensioners-have-lowest-life-expectancy-in-uk-with-birkenhead-oaps-not-far-behind-100252-25322826|title=Bootle pensioners have shortest life expectancy in UK with Birkenhead OAPs also in bottom ten|publisher=Wirral News|date=4 December 2009|accessdate=4 December 2009|first=Jo|last=Kelly|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110809192557/http://www.wirralnews.co.uk/wirral-news/local-wirral-news/2009/12/04/bootle-pensioners-have-lowest-life-expectancy-in-uk-with-birkenhead-oaps-not-far-behind-100252-25322826/|archivedate=9 August 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> Birkenhead is served by [[Wirral University Teaching Hospital NHS Foundation Trust]] (through its [[Arrowe Park Hospital]], [[St Catherine's Health Centre]] and [[Clatterbridge Hospital]] sites) and Wirral [[Primary Care Trust]]. Formerly, Birkenhead was also served by [[Birkenhead General Hospital]] on Park Road North and St. James' Hospital in Claughton, now demolished and redeveloped for housing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/hospitalrecords/details.asp?id=816&page=58|title= St James' Hospital, Birkenhead|publisher=National archives|accessdate=11 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Arts and leisure==\n\n===Arts===\nThe [[Laird School of Art]] was the first public school of art outside London and was given to the town by John Laird. It opened on 27 September 1871. The [[Williamson Art Gallery and Museum|Williamson Art Gallery]] was opened in 1928 and houses a fine collection of paintings, porcelain and pottery.\n\nIn 1856, Birkenhead Library was opened as the country's first public library in an [[Unincorporated area|unincorporated]] borough.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.visitliverpool.com/site/product-p44389|title=Birkenhead Central Library|publisher=visitliverpool.com|accessdate=14 January 2008}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\nThe library was situated in Hamilton Street until 1909, when it moved to a new building in Market Street South,<ref name=Bidston23>{{harvnb|Bidston|1978|page=23}}</ref> near Birkenhead Market. In the 1930s, this building (along with much of the surrounding area) was demolished to make way for the entrance to the [[Queensway Tunnel]]. The present library, [[Birkenhead Central Library]], is situated on Borough Road and was opened by [[George V of the United Kingdom|King George V]] in 1934.<ref name=Bidston23 />\n\nDespite being in England, Birkenhead (known as ''Penbedw'', in Welsh) hosted Wales' [[National Eisteddfod]] in 1917<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.archiveshub.ac.uk/aug04e.shtml|title=Title page of the 1917 Welsh National Eisteddfod programme held at Birkenhead|publisher=Archives Hub|accessdate=18 February 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070525192426/http://www.archiveshub.ac.uk/aug04e.shtml|archivedate=25 May 2007}}</ref> as well as an unofficial National Eisteddfod event in 1879. As in Liverpool,<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/northeast/sites/history/pages/liverpool.shtml|title=The Liverpool Welsh|publisher=BBC Wales|date=7 January 2008|accessdate=14 January 2008}}</ref> migrants from Wales, especially North Wales, contributed greatly to the growth of the town and its cultural development in the 19th century. The first local Birkenhead Eisteddfod, a precursor of the national events, took place in 1864.<ref>{{cite book|title=Liverpool 800: Culture, Character & History|editor=John Belchem|year=2006|isbn=1-84631-035-0}}</ref> The 1917 National Eisteddfod was notable for the award of the chair to the poet Ellis Humphrey Evans, known as [[Hedd Wyn]]. The winner was announced, and the crowd waited for the winner to accept congratulations before the chairing ceremony, but no winner appeared. It was then announced that Hedd Wyn had been killed the previous month on the battlefield in Belgium, and the bardic chair was draped in black. These events were portrayed in the [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] nominated film ''[[Hedd Wyn (film)|Hedd Wyn]]'', and were apparently intended as a protest against the war policies of [[Prime Minister of the UK|Prime Minister]] [[David Lloyd George]], who was present. There is a commemorative stone for the event in Birkenhead Park.<ref>{{cite book|first=Stephen J.|last=Roberts|title=A History of Wirral|year=2002|isbn=978-1-86077-512-3}}</ref> The first meeting of the international [[Celtic Congress]] also took place at the Birkenhead Eisteddfod.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.evertype.com/celtcong/cc-hist-mellis.html |title=A short history of the Celtic Congress|first=Mari|last=Ellis|accessdate=3 October 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080602125805/http://www.evertype.com/celtcong/cc-hist-mellis.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2 June 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Argyle Theatre]] was a major theatre and music hall which opened on 28 December 1868<ref name=Bidston19 /> and became notable for the calibre of artistes who appeared there. Later in its life, it was also used as a cinema. The theatre was destroyed by bombing in 1940.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.arthurlloyd.co.uk/BirkenheadTheatres.htm|title=Birkenhead, Wirral, Theatres and Halls|publisher=arthurlloyd.co.uk|accessdate=16 July 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Theatre Royal'', opened on 31 October 1864, was in Argyle Street and had a capacity of 1,850.<ref name=Bidston19 /> This theatre was closed in 1919 and demolished in the 1930s.<ref name=Bidston19 /> Another theatre, the ''Hippodrome'', which was converted into a cinema in the 1930s, stood on the site of what became the [[The Co-operative Group|Co-operative]] department store in Grange Road.<ref name=Bidston20>{{harvnb|Bidston|1978|page=20}}</ref>\n\nThe Little Theatre was established in 1958 from a converted former [[Presbyterian]] church whilst, more recently, the Pacific Road Arts Centre in Woodside opened in 1999.\n\n===Media===\nBirkenhead is served by the ''[[Liverpool Echo]]'' local daily newspaper. The free local weekly newspapers are the ''Wirral Globe'' and the ''Birkenhead News'' (part of the Wirral News group).\n\nThe local radio station [[Heart Wirral]] is based in offices at the Pacific Road Arts Centre. In addition, there are five other local radio stations that transmit to Birkenhead: [[BBC Radio Merseyside]], [[Radio City 96.7]], [[Greatest Hits Liverpool]], [[Capital Liverpool]] and [[City Talk 105.9|CityTalk]].\n\nBirkenhead is situated within the television regions of [[BBC]] North West and [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]'s [[Granada Television]]. The local television station [[Bay TV Liverpool]] also broadcasts to the area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wirralglobe.co.uk/news/11646943.Bay_TV_Liverpool_to_make_a_splash_today/|title=Bay TV Liverpool to make a splash today|work=Wirral Globe|date=4 December 2014|accessdate=2 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Leisure===\nAs well as Birkenhead Park, other recreational open spaces in Birkenhead include Mersey Park and Victoria Park. [[Arrowe Park]] is a large area of parkland at the western edge of the town. In 1929, the [[3rd World Scout Jamboree]] was held there.\n\nThe first two [[Scouting|Boy Scout]] groups in the world are thought to have been founded as the 1st and 2nd Birkenhead groups at [[YMCA]] on the same night in 1908.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://2ndbirkenhead.webs.com/|title=Home|website=2nd Birkenhead Scout Group|access-date=2018-11-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181112101413/https://2ndbirkenhead.webs.com/|archive-date=12 November 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> The 2nd Birkenhead Scout Group is still operating and therefore is the longest running scout group in the world.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\n===Sport===\nThe first known [[association football|football]]  club on the Wirral was Birkenhead F.C. which was founded in 1879 by Robert E. Lythgoe, a former [[Druids F.C.]] player. Other clubs included Belmont Football Club, founded in 1884.  They adopted the name [[Tranmere Rovers F.C.]] the following year, and are a professional team who play at [[Prenton Park]] near the Tranmere area of the town. They were a founder member of [[Football League Third Division North|Division Three North]] in 1921, and were a member of [[The Football League]] until 2015, when they were relegated to the [[Football Conference|Conference]], the fifth tier of English football. They returned to the Football League three seasons later, after a 2-1 play off final win against [[Boreham Wood F.C.]].  (An unrelated, disbanded side had played under the name \"Tranmere Rovers Cricket Club (Association football section)\" in 1881\u201382.) [[Cammell Laird 1907 F.C.]] is the town's semi-professional [[association football|football]] club who play at Kirklands in Rock Ferry. They play in the [[North West Counties League]] Division One.\n\nThe [[Birkenhead Park FC|Birkenhead Park Football Club]] was founded in 1871, the same year as the [[Rugby Football Union]]. The club originally played in the Lower Park but moved to their current home in the Upper Park in 1885.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pitchero.com/clubs/birkenheadpark/a/a-brief-history-of-birkenhead-park-41151.html |title=A BRIEF HISTORY OF BIRKENHEAD PARK|work=Pitchero|accessdate=23 November 2015}}</ref> Birkenhead Park also has its own [[cricket]] club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pitchero.com/clubs/birkenheadparkcricketclub|title=Welcome|work=Pitchero|accessdate=1 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nLocated in the town are the Birkenhead North End and Victoria Cycling Clubs. Olympic riders from the clubs include [[Chris Boardman]], [[Mark Bell (cyclist)|Mark Bell]], [[Steve Cummings]] and [[Rachel Heal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bnecc.co.uk/about_us.htm|title=Birkenhead North End Cycling Club Olympians|accessdate=18 February 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071008215259/http://www.bnecc.co.uk/about_us.htm|archivedate=8 October 2007|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://fp.marklw.plus.com/htdocs/bvcc/theclub/history.htm|title=Birkenhead Victoria Cycling Club history |accessdate=18 February 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050107022728/http://fp.marklw.plus.com/htdocs/bvcc/theclub/history.htm|archivedate=7 January 2005}}</ref>\n\nBirkenhead has been host to various [[Rowing (sport)|rowing]] clubs since 1840.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.merseyrc.com/page11.htm|title=The History of Mersey Rowing Club: Founded 1854|work=Mersey Rowing Club|accessdate=5 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160505062910/http://www.merseyrc.com/page11.htm|archive-date=5 May 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> At present, Liverpool Victoria Rowing Club operates from a facility at the western end of West Float.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.britishrowing.org/club/liverpool-victoria-rc/|title=Liverpool Victoria RC|work=British Rowing|accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Cultural references==\nBirkenhead is mentioned in the song \"What She Said\" on the album ''[[Meat Is Murder]]'' by [[the Smiths]]: ''What she read/All heady books/She'd sit and prophesise{{not a typo}}/(It took a tattooed boy from Birkenhead/To really really open her eyes).''\n\nThe town is also referred to in the song \"Everything Is Sorrow\" on the [[The Boo Radleys|Boo Radleys]]' ''[[C'mon Kids]]'' album: ''I worked in Birkenhead for you/It brings me tears even now.''\n\nA fairly detailed description of the town is given in [[Paul O'Grady]]'s memoirs, ''At My Mother's Knee ... and Other Low Joints: The Autobiography''.\n\nBirkenhead is indirectly referenced by \"''the Birken'ead drill''\" in [[Rudyard Kipling]]'s poem \"Soldier an' Sailor Too\": ''To take your chance in the thick of a rush, with firing all about, / Is nothing so bad when you've cover to 'and, an' leave an' likin' to shout; / But to stand an' be still to the Birken'ead drill is a damn tough bullet to chew, / An' they done it, the Jollies \u2013 'Er Majesty's Jollies \u2013 soldier an' sailor too!'', as it refers to heroism by Royal Marines during the sinking of [[HMS Birkenhead (1845)|HMS Birkenhead]], itself named after the town in which it was built.  [[HMS Birkenhead (1845)#Aftermath|Other authors]] have done this as well.\n\nThe 1998 book, [[Awaydays]], and the following 2009 film of the same name are set in Birkenhead.\n\n==Notable people==\n===Actors and performers===\nIn the arts, Birkenhead has produced several actors and performers including [[Lionel Gamlin]], [[Glenda Jackson]],<ref name=\"liverpoolecho.co.uk\">http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/all-about/birkenhead</ref> [[Lewis Collins]], [[Megs Jenkins]], [[Taron Egerton]], [[Patricia Routledge]], [[Paul O'Grady]] (also known as [[Lily Savage]]) and soprano [[Valerie Masterson]]. The dancer and actor [[Lindsay Kemp]] was born in the town but as a child moved to [[South Shields]].<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/features/lindsay-kemp-how-the-lost-boy-of-dance-found-his-feet-9188679.html  Nadine Meisner, \"Lindsay Kemp: How the lost boy of dance found his feet\", ''The Independent'', 28 January 2002]. Retrieved 25 August 2018</ref>\n\n===Artists===\nSome notable artists were born in the town, such as [[Philip Wilson Steer]], [[Robert Talbot Kelly]], [[Tom Palin]], [[Bessie Bamber]], [[Annie R. Merrylees Arnold]], the workers at the [[Della Robbia Pottery]] and two cartoonists: [[Norman Thelwell]] and [[Bill Tidy]].<ref>https://www.pressreader.com/uk/cheshire-life/20181001/283025465549093</ref>\n\n===Authors and journalists===\nIt has also produced poets and authors such as [[A.S.J. Tessimond]], [[Adrian Henri]] and Michael Z. Williamson. The [[World War I]] poet [[Wilfred Owen]], though born in [[Oswestry]], lived in Birkenhead from the age of 4 and was educated at the Birkenhead Institute High School (now demolished). [[Andreas Whittam Smith]], founder editor of ''[[The Independent]]'', grew up in Birkenhead, where his father was an [[Anglican]] clergyman.<ref>{{citation|title=Why I am Still an Anglican|publisher=Continuum|year=2006|page=67}}</ref>\n\n===Musicians===\nThere are several musicians linked to the area. [[Freddie Marks]] from [[Rod, Jane and Freddy]] was born in Birkenhead, as was [[John Gorman (entertainer)|John Gorman]] of [[The Scaffold]]. Indie band [[Half Man Half Biscuit]] hail from Birkenhead, as did boogie-rock band [[Engine (boogie-rock band)|Engine]], [[Paul Heaton]], lead singer of the [[Housemartins]] and the [[Beautiful South]], singer/songwriter [[Charlie Landsborough]] and [[Desmond Briscoe]] co-founder and original manager of the pioneering [[BBC Radiophonic Workshop]]. [[Elvis Costello]] moved to Birkenhead in 1971 with his mother,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/whats-on/music-nightlife-news/elvis-costello-publish-memoirs-8954761|first=Jade|last=Wright|title=Elvis Costello to publish his memoirs|work=Liverpool Echo|date=31 March 2015|accessdate=29 October 2015}}</ref> who was from Liverpool, although Elvis Costello's father was himself from Birkenhead. [[Tony Friel]] (bassist from [[The Fall (band)|the Fall]] and [[The Passage (band)|the Passage]]), synthpop musician [[David Hughes (musician)|David Hughes]] (of [[Dalek I Love You]], [[Orchestral Manoeuvres in the Dark]] and [[Godot (band)|Godot]]) and [[Malcolm Holmes]] (drummer with pop group [[Orchestral Manoeuvres in the Dark]]) were born there. [[David Balfe]] (music manager, and member of Dalek I Love You, [[Big in Japan (band)|Big in Japan]], [[the Teardrop Explodes]]) attended primary and secondary school there. [[Miles Kane]], musician, singer and songwriter and member of [[The Last Shadow Puppets]] and [[The Rascals (English band)|The Rascals]], was born in the town.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n\n===Politicians and public figures===\n[[File:The Rt Hon. Frederick Edwin Smith, 1st Earl of Birkenhead in 1915.jpg|thumb|[[F. E. Smith, 1st Earl of Birkenhead]]]]\n[[F. E. Smith, 1st Earl of Birkenhead]], a leading Conservative politician of the early 20th century, was born in the town, as were [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] politician [[Malcolm Bruce]], [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] politician [[Stephen Ladyman]], the prominent [[occult]]ist [[Alex Sanders (Wiccan)|Alex Sanders]], and [[Tony Hall, Baron Hall of Birkenhead]], the [[Director-General of the BBC]].\n\n===Scientists and technologists===\nAerodynamicists [[Gwen Alston]] and [[Melvill Jones]] were born in Birkenhead, as was [[David Pearson (computer scientist)|David Pearson]] hitech pioneer. Also born in Birkenhead was [[Henry Herbert Collier]], inventor and founder of the [[Matchless]] motorcycle marque.\n\n===Soldiers and explorers===\n[[Sandy Irvine]], a participant of the [[1924 British Mount Everest expedition]], was born in Birkenhead. There has been speculation that [[George Mallory]] and he reached the summit. Similarly, [[Alan Rouse]], a mountaineer who died in the [[1986 K2 disaster]], was educated in Birkenhead. [[Daniel Poole]], a recipient of the [[Distinguished Conduct Medal]] during [[World War I]] was born in the town.<ref name=ADB>Foldi, N.S. (1978). [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A110261b.htm Poole, Daniel (1882\u20131959)']. [[Australian Dictionary of Biography]], Volume 11, Melbourne University Press, p. 255. Retrieved on 9 August 2009.</ref>\n\n===Sports people===\nBirkenhead has also produced notable sportsmen such as [[Matt Dawson]], the [[rugby union]] player; [[William Ralph Dean|'Dixie' Dean]] ([[Everton F.C.]]),<ref name=\"liverpoolecho.co.uk\"/> record-breaking footballer, who was born at 313 Laird Street; and several other footballers including [[Peter Davenport]], [[Jason McAteer]], [[David Thompson (footballer, born 1977)|David Thompson]], [[Max Power (footballer)|Max]] [[Max Power (footballer)|Power]], [[Jodie Taylor]] England Lionesses International .The football manager [[Nigel Adkins]] also hails from the town International relations.\n\n==Twin towns==\nBirkenhead is [[Town twinning|twinned]], as a part of [[Metropolitan Borough of Wirral|Wirral]], with:\n*{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Gennevilliers]], France\n*{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Latina, Lazio]], Italy\n*{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Lorient]], France\n\n===Twin towns \u2013 Sister cities===\nBirkenhead also has a [[Sister City|Sister City Agreement]] with:\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Midland, Texas|Midland]], [[Texas]], United States<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.wirral.gov.uk/LGCL/100009/200096/662/content_0002058.html|archive-url=https://archive.is/20070703053914/http://www.wirral.gov.uk/LGCL/100009/200096/662/content_0002058.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=3 July 2007|title=Town Twinning|publisher=Metropolitan Borough of Wirral|accessdate=14 January 2008|isbn=92-827-8272-7}}</ref>\n\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in the United Kingdom}}\n\n==Future==\nThe major redevelopment project under consideration is [[Peel Holdings]]' \"[[Wirral Waters]]\". This would allow for \u00a34.5&nbsp;billion of investment in the regeneration of the dockland area. This equates with an investment of over \u00a314,000 for each of the 320,000 residents of the Wirral. At the [[Great Float|East Float]] and [[Vittoria Dock]], the development would include several 50-storey skyscrapers, {{convert|5000000|sqft|m2|-3}} of new office space and {{convert|11000000|sqft|m2}} for new residential flats. A retail and leisure quarter at the former [[Bidston Dock]] site would encompass another {{convert|571000|sqft|m2|-2}} of space. The whole project would create more than 27,000 permanent new jobs, aside from the employment required for construction and other peripheral employment. The development would be expected to take up to thirty years.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.peel.co.uk/peelholdings/source/newsdetails.asp?type=1&page=1&newsid=122|title=Peel unveil plans for \u00a34.5 billion \"Wirral Waters\" scheme|publisher=Peel Holdings|date=5 September 2006|accessdate=14 January 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071011034738/http://www.peel.co.uk/peelholdings/source/newsdetails.asp?type=1&page=1&newsid=122 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 11 October 2007}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Listed buildings in Birkenhead]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n*{{cite book|title=Birkenhead in Times Past|first=Carol E.|last=Bidston|publisher=Countryside Publications Ltd.|location=Chorley|year=1978|isbn=0861570030|oclc=16480899|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|title=Birkenhead Through Time|first=Ian|last=Collard|publisher=Amberley|year=2012|isbn=9781848689657|oclc=934954016|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book| title=The Wirral Railway and its Predecessors| year=2009| first=T.B. |last=Maund| publisher=Lightmoor Press| isbn=978-1-899889-38-9|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|first1=Nikolaus|last1=Pevsner|authorlink1=Nikolaus Pevsner|first2=Edward|last2=Hubbard|authorlink2=Edward Hubbard|title=Cheshire|series=The Buildings of England|publisher=Penguin|year=1971|isbn=9780140710427|oclc=521341|ref=harv}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|title=Birkenhead and its Surroundings|first=Henry Kelsall|last=Aspinall|publisher=The Liverpool Booksellers' Co. Ltd.|location=Liverpool|date=1903|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S3IKAwAAQBAJ|oclc=33990938}}\n*{{cite book|title=Yesterday's Wirral: Birkenhead, Prenton and Oxton|first1=Ian|last1=Boumphrey|first2=Marilyn|last2=Boumphrey|publisher=Ian & Marilyn Boumphrey|year=1981|isbn=9780950725512|oclc=16599808}}\n*{{cite book|title=Birkenhead: A Pictorial History|first=Ian|last=Boumphrey|publisher=Phillmore|year=1995|isbn=9780850339888|oclc=36548684}}\n*{{cite book|title=Yesterday's Birkenhead|first=Ian|last=Boumphrey|publisher=The author|year=2007a|isbn=9781899241262}}\n*{{cite book|title=Birkenhead at War 1939-45|first=Ian|last=Boumphrey|publisher=Ian & Marilyn Boumphrey|year=2007b|isbn=9781899241163|oclc=650238915}}\n*{{cite book|title=Annals of the Liverpool Stage|pp=377\u2013386|first=R.J.|last=Broadbent|publisher=Edward Howell|location=Liverpool|year=1908|url=https://archive.org/stream/cu31924026123822#page/n437/mode/2up/search/birkenhead}}\n*{{cite book|title=Birkenhead: An Illustrated History|first=Ralph T.|last=Brocklebank|publisher=Breedon|year=2003|isbn=9781859833506|oclc=56469838}}\n*{{cite book|title=Birkenhead from old photographs|first=Ian|last=Collard|publisher=Amberley|year=2010|isbn=9781848685796|oclc=503647633}}\n*{{cite book|title=Birkenhead: A History|first=Elizabeth|last=Davey|publisher=The History Press|year=2013|isbn=9780750955522|oclc=316434050}}\n*{{cite book|title=Memories of the chronicles of Birkenhead|first=Hilda|last=Gamlin|publisher=E. Howell|year=1892|oclc=866209732}}\n*{{cite book|title=A Century of Birkenhead and Wirral|first=Cliff|last=Hayes|publisher=Sutton|year=2007|isbn=9780750949040|oclc=520460751}}\n*{{cite book|title=Birkenhead Shipbuilding|first=Alan G.|last=Jones|publisher=Fast Print|year=2011|isbn= \t9781780352114|oclc=773368902}}\n*{{cite book|title=Bygone Birkenhead|first=J.R.|last=Kaighin|publisher=Wilmer|year=1925|oclc=77304339}}\n*{{cite book|title=Birkenhead, 1877-1974|first=Myrra|last=Lea|publisher=County Borough of Birkenhead|year=1974|isbn=9780904582000|oclc=1365533}}\n*{{cite book|title=Meat at Woodside: Birkenhead Livestock Trade, 1878-1981|first=Ken|last=McCarron|publisher=Merseyside Port Folios|year=1991|isbn=9780951612927|oclc=26313657}}\n*{{cite book|title=Birkenhead yesterday and today|first=W.R.S.|last=McIntyre|publisher=Philip|year=1948|oclc=504769644}}\n*{{cite book|title=The History of the Hundred of Wirral|first=William Williams|last=Mortimer|year=1847|publisher=Whittaker & Co.|location=London|url=https://archive.org/stream/historyhundredw01mortgoog#page/n346/mode/2up|id=pp305\u2013405|oclc=4976662}}\n*{{cite book|title=Reminiscences of Birkenhead|first=Charles Grey|last=Mott|publisher=H. Young and Sons|year=1900|isbn=|oclc=12987941}}\n*{{cite book|title=Report on Secondary Education in Birkenhead|first=Michael E.|last=Sadler|publisher=George Philip & Son Ltd.|location=London|year=1904|url=https://archive.org/stream/reportonseconda04sadlgoog#page/n5/mode/2up}}\n*{{cite book|title=History of ancient and m